<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton Departs Moscow for Minsk </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1501080494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0759 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1501080494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Vladimir Taranov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 15 TASS--U.S. President Bill Clinton 
and his wife have just left here by air for Minsk at the close 
of a three-day official visit to Russia. 
  The chief result of the Russian-U.S. talks in Moscow is in 
the signing of a Moscow declaration by the two presidents, the 
declaration which reaffirmed the importance of Russian-U.S. 
cooperation for global stability, as well as in a joint Russo- 
American-Ukrainian agreement on the removal of nuclear weapons 
from Ukraine's territory. The agreement became a breakthrough 
in the field of non-proliferation of nuclear weapons. 
  In all, 12 bilateral documents were adopted during the 
summit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

