<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   White House Official Sums Up Results of Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1501005894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1812 
GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1501005894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Aleksey Berezhkov] </F>
  [Excerpts] Moscow, 14 Jan--U.S. President Bill Clinton's 
visit to Moscow was packed with important talks, meetings with 
public and political figures, and protocol events. [passage 
omitted] 
  At a routine briefing today, a high-ranking White House 
spokesman, who asked not to be named, summed up the preliminary 
results of the Moscow summit. He said that President Bill 
Clinton had fulfilled the tasks before him: to confirm 
partnership relations between the United States and Russia that 
were established in Vancouver, to express firm support by the 
United States for the economic and political reforms in Russia, 
and also to develop ties with a wider spectrum of political 
forces in the country. 
  According to the briefer, the main themes of the talks in 
Moscow were economic reforms in Russia, the "Partnership for 
Peace" program, and also disarmament. The White House spokesman 
said that the most important event was, perhaps, the signing 
this morning of a trilateral agreement between Russia, Ukraine, 
and the United States on eliminating nuclear weapons deployed on 
Ukrainian territory. 
  He said also that the leaders of both countries had 
discussed 
both yesterday and today the question of the presence of Russian 
troops in Latvia and Estonia. "We think that progress has been 
made in this area and very much hope that agreements on troop 
withdrawal will be concluded soon between Russia and Latvia and 
between Russia and Estonia," the White House spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

