<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Adviser Hails Success of Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701162294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1609 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1701162294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 17 TASS -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin's top adviser academician Andranik Migranyan hailed the 
success of the U.S.-Russian summit meeting that was held in 
Moscow last week. 
  Commenting on the achievements of the summit meeting 
Migranyan said that "the president of Russia admitted the need 
to seek a new architecture of European security, saying that the 
partnership for peace concept born within the NATO is not the 
only possibility." By this he indirectly admitted the need to 
establish such a system of European security in which all 
countries of eastern Europe would have equal rights in adopting 
decisions to maintain peace and stability, the academician said. 
  Secondly, the U.S. side confirmed "Russia's special role in 
maintaining stability on the territory of the post-Soviet 
space," Migranyan said, referring to the U.S.-Russian-Ukrainian 
agreement to eliminate Ukrainian nuclear weapons. 
  Additionally, "the U.S. President went further than making 
declarations and or giving advice, he concluded concrete 
agreements with Russia to open the American market to Russian 
goods and include russia into the GATT as an equal member," as 
well as integrate it into other international financial and 
economic structures. 
  The academician also welcomed Clinton's decision to help 
defend the rights of Russian minorities in the Baltic states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

