<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Holds News Conference in Moscow 14 Jan </TI></H3>
<H4>   Greets Deal as `Historic' </H4>
<F P=102> LD1401143294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1412 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401143294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Vladimir Taranov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 14 TASS -- Ukrainian President Leonid 
Kravchuk expressed satisfaction with his meeting with Russian 
and U.S. Presidents Boris Yeltsin and Bill Clinton here on 
Friday [14 January]. 
  "This is a historic moment," he said at a news conference at 
the Ukrainian Embassy in Moscow, noting that "Ukraine, along 
with other states, is marching along the road of nuclear 
disarmament." 
  In Kravchuk's opinion, the joint Russian-American-Ukrainian 
agreement, signed in Moscow, on the withdrawal of nuclear 
weapons from Ukraine gives it a guarantee of security and will 
help to receive compensation in nuclear fuel. 
  The agreement will also help to step up economic relations 
with other countries. The withdrawal of strategic nuclear 
weapons from Ukraine is based on the Russian-Ukrainian treaty. 
  As for tactical nuclear weapons withdrawn from the republic, 
Russian, U.S. and Ukrainian experts will have to determine their 
value, the Ukrainian president stressed. 
  Later, Ukraine will be compensated in the form of 
subtraction 
from Ukrainian debts to Russia for energy carriers. 
  Noting that Russian-Ukrainian relations were given a new 
impetus, Kravchuk expressed confidence that the problem of the 
Black Sea Fleet will be settled in 1994 and "then our countries 
will have a good prospect for the future". 
  "In geopolitical respect, we have to live on this earth of 
ours, and there is no other way out," the Ukrainian president 
stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

