<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Minister Says U.S. Still Discriminates Against Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1501213794 Moscow Radio Moscow in Russian to Tajikistan 
1700 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1501213794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Radio Slavyanka" program of the Russian Defense </F>
Ministry] 
  [Text] Despite significant progress in Russian-U.S. trade 
and economic relations, they are not yet free from the legacy of 
the Cold War, Oleg Davydov, Russia's minister for foreign 
economic relations, told Itar-Tass in Moscow. 
  He recalled that United States has not yet canceled the 
Jackson-Venik amendment which discriminates against Russia. The 
solution of a number of financial and commercial issues is tied 
to various political conditions and to progress in the 
implementation of market reforms in Russia. 
  The minister added that the policy of strict quantitative 
regulation of Russian imports is still in force. Russia, in the 
opinion of Oleg Davydov, should first and foremost seek the 
lifting of restrictions on the export of its goods to the United 
States and develop a mechanism for bilateral consultations. 

</TEXT>

