<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pickering Reiterates U.S. Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701191294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1807 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1701191294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The American administration has been following 
developments in the Russian leadership. A more detailed 
reaction can be expected from Washington after the official 
announcement of the makeup of a new Russian government, the U.S. 
ambassador in Moscow Thomas Pickering declared in an interview 
with Interfax on Monday. 
  He explained that his administration's position towards 
Russia's reforms did not depend on concrete personalities but 
was based on the principles they advocated. 
  Commenting on the First Vice Premier Yegor Gaydar's decision 
to resign, Pickering said that it did not take Washington aback, 
since rumors on Gaydar's possible resignation from the 
government had circulated long before his public announcement 
about it. 
  He voiced satisfaction with Gaydar's intention to carry on 
his duties in the Duma, where he led one of the major 
parliamentary factions, "Russia's Choice." 
  Pickering said that in the current situation the American 
administration regarded President Yeltsin's attitude to further 
reform as crucial. He recalled that at the recent summit, U.S. 
President Clinton had been firmly assured by Yeltsin that reform 
in Russia would be continued and stability there would be 
preserved. 

</TEXT>

