<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Stresses Importance of Geneva Talks on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701185194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1807 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1701185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The next meeting of the warring Bosnian sides to be 
held in Geneva on Tuesday is "extremely important; it may prove 
to be decisive from the viewpoint of viability of the present 
plan for a settlement in Bosnia-Herzegovina." The special envoy 
of Russia's president, Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin, 
said so in an interview with INTERFAX before his departure for 
Geneva. 
  According to him, "very intensive" consultations were 
conducted in the past few days in the framework of preparations 
for the Geneva round of talks. This issue was discussed at the 
meeting between the Russian and American Presidents in Moscow, 
and at the parallel negotiations between Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher and the head of Russian diplomacy, Andrey 
Kozyrev. 
  According to the diplomat, progress reached in the talks on 
territorial concessions is the principal positive factor in the 
efforts to resolve the crisis. Some 33.5 percent of the 
territory in Bosnia-Herzegovina claimed by the Muslims have been 
guaranteed to them at last. It was a key demand of the European 
Union, and a top- priority issue at the talks, Churkin said. 

</TEXT>

