<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Paper Cites UK `Caution' on Bosnia Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1401132994 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 14 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM1401132994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Sergey Sidorov report under "Yesterday" rubric: "UK </F>
Defense Secretary Favors Cautious NATO Approach to Bosnia"] 
  [Text] NATO should show great caution regarding potential 
air strikes in Bosnia and Herzegovina. This opinion was 
expressed in an interview on BBC radio by UK Defense Secretary 
Malcolm Rifkind, commenting on the decisions of the session of 
the North Atlantic bloc council which has ended in Brussels. He 
stressed that London feels no special enthusiasm for the policy 
of intimidation by air strikes because British servicemen form 
part of the NATO forces on the ground engaged in delivering 
humanitarian aid to the population. 
  Ending the war in former Yugoslavia is not the task of the 
United Nations: It cannot be achieved by military measures from 
outside, the head of the military department pointed out. The 
international contingent's objective is to ensure the normal 
delivery of humanitarian aid to tens of thousands of innocent 
people. 

</TEXT>

