<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Submarines Being Sold to DPRK for Scrap Metal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1701140494 Vladivostok Radiostantsiya Tikhiy Okean 
Maritime Network in Russian 0815 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1701140494 </F>
<F P=104>  Vladivostok Radiostantsiya Tikhiy Okean 
Maritime Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Pacific Ocean" Program] </F>
  [Text] Four Russian submarines, currently in the Pacific 
Fleet, will leave Russian territorial waters in the near future 
to join the naval forces of North Korea. TOKYO SHIMBUN 
newspaper reported in its evening issue [date not given] that a 
contract on export of the submarines has already been signed by 
representatives of Moscow and Pyongyang. Quoting a high-ranking 
source in the Pacific Fleet command, the newspaper claims that 
talks with North Korea on delivery of four submarines have been 
conducted by representatives of the Russian naval forces in 
complete secrecy. 
  The sum of contract is not known. Currently, the submarines 
schedule to leave for DPRK are being used for training purposes 
and are practically unsuitable for combat missions. They were 
all built in the sixties. A source in the Pacific Fleet command 
assessed that after necessary repairs, the submarines would join 
the North Korean combat subunits. However, it is not out of 
the question that they would be dismantled, and the spare parts 
used to repair other North Korean submarines. 

</TEXT>

