<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Specialists' on Reusing Submarines </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1701164594 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 18 Jan 94 First 
Edition p 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1701164594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Aleksandr Sychev report: "Kim Il-song Has Bought From Us </F>
Submarines That Cannot Sail"] 
  [Text] North Korea is experiencing an acute shortage of 
raw materials for smelting steel and is purchasing old weapons 
for scrap whenever the opportunity arises. Four Russian 
submarines are destined for that country's metallurgical plants 
in the near future. 
  The submarines in question are SS-60's, known in the West by 
the designation "Foxtrot." These diesel-powered torpedo-armed 
submarines were constructed in the Soviet Union in the 1960's 
and have already completed their intended service life. Of the 
40 or so submarines of this class which remain in the Russian 
Navy, some are still used as training vessels. The rest, 
however, are permanently laid up and are quietly poisoning the 
environment at naval bases. 
  Navy commanders have been authorized to sell off these 
decommissioned vessels on their own initiative. Because Russia 
lacks adequate production capacity suited to preparing warships 
for melting down, and also because the country's economic 
position boosts the attractiveness of freely convertible 
currency, foreign buyers naturally have priority rights. 
  The contract to sell four decommissioned submarines to North 
Korean buyers was signed by the Russian Pacific Fleet command. 
  The Japanese newspaper TOKYO SHIMBUN has conjectured that, 
having obtained the submarines, North Korea will carry out 
repairs and put them into service in its navy. In the opinion 
of Russian specialists, however, it would be economically 
disadvantageous to carry out a complete overhaul of the 
"Foxtrots." Moreover, under existing rules all armaments and 
guidance systems will be dismantled before the submarines are 
dispatched to North Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-56410 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov011_a_94053" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-011 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

