<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Premier's Cabinet Concept Seen Diverging From Yeltsin's </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK1501120094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 15 Jan 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK1501120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Ivan Zasurskiy report under the "Government" rubric: </F>
"Boris Fedorov's Fate as an Indicator. The Goals of the Prime 
Minister and Those of the President Diverge Again"] 
  [Text] After Boris Yeltsin appointed Anatoliy Chubays 
deputy prime minister, bypassing a lengthy process of forming a 
government, the question of differences between the prime 
minister and the president has taken on a new intensity. Did 
the prime minister know about Anatoliy Chubays' appointment? If 
not, then the war of position inside the executive branch is 
becoming clearly threatening in nature: The president is 
betting everything, and this suggests that the old cabinet's 
volatile balance will remain in the new one. Apparently, soon we 
should expect Boris Fedorov's appointment. This, in turn, will 
mean the reemergence of characteristics of the old confrontation 
-- the Finance Ministry against the Central Bank and the 
government against the parliament ("Russia's Choice" will not be 
able to take the budget commission under control). 
  The only thing one can state with assurance so far is that 
the prime minister's line toward forming a manageable and 
effective government will depend on his consultations with the 
president that are to follow Anatoliy Chubays' appointment and 
will be under way until Monday. The goals of the president and 
those of the prime minister have somewhat diverged. 
Chernomyrdin needs hard-working, not politicized, executives. 
Yeltsin, apparently, needs a steady reform course. 
  Boris Fedorov's fate will be a decisive indicator at this 
stage. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

