<H3> <TI>   Aims to Work With Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1601115294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1055 
GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1601115294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Velichko] </F>
  [Excerpts] Moscow, 16 Jan -- "I am forced to decline an 
offer from the chairman of the Government, and I am not 
accepting the post of first vice premier." This was stated by 
Yegor Gaydar at a meeting with journalists today. He added that 
he cannot be in the government and in opposition to it at the 
same time. [passage omitted] 
  At the same time, Yegor Gaydar spoke out for continuing to 
work with the Government. Touching upon the question of 
personalities, the leader of the "Russia's Choice" also spoke 
out for joining Grigoriy Yavlinskiy's government [as received]. 
[Moscow ITAR-TASS in English at 1214 GMT on 16 January, in a 
similar item, renders this sentence as: "Gaydar came out for 
Grigoriy Yavlinskiy to join the government."] 
  The leader of the "Russia's Choice" told journalists that he 
spoke with Boris Yeltsin on 13 January before making his 
decision not to join the new Government. 
  Yegor Gaydar said that he intends to "concentrate his 
attention on work in the State Duma." He noted that in this 
connection "Russia's Choice" intends to do everything possible 
not to allow representatives of the Liberal Democratic Party to 
join the key committees of the lower chamber -- that is the 
committees for defense, security, and international policy. 

</TEXT>

