<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Accepts Gaydar's Resignation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701131394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1304 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1701131394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 17 TASS -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin accepted the resignation of the architect of Russian 
reform, First Deputy Prime Minister Yegor Gaydar on Monday and 
assured that reforms in the country will continue. 
  "Giving tribute to the competence, courage and the 
contribution which Yegor Gaydar made into the course of economic 
reform, I understand the arguments and motives which made him 
offer to resign", Yeltsin said in a statement received by TASS. 
  "Accepting this resignation I would like to stress the 
irreversibility of the course of reform aimed at a deep and 
democratic transformation of the Russian society, its economy 
and political institutions. The policy of reform will continue 
proceeding from democratic principles which are the basis of the 
new Russian Constitution and with account, first and foremost, 
of the national and strategic Russian interests", the president 
said. 
  "I express conviction that while working in the State Duma 
Yegor Gaydar will proceed from the supreme interests of serving 
Russia like he did in his previous activities", according to the 
statement distributed by presidential spokesman Vyacheslav 
Kostikov. 
  This is the second time that Gaydar has to abandon his post 
in the government. In December 1992 Yeltsin replaced him with 
Viktor Chernomyrdin after a severe conflict with the parliament 
on the course of reform. 
  Gaydar returned to the government as first deputy premier in 
the middle of September 1993. 
  After December 12 parliamentary elections Yeltsin said at a 
press conference that Gaydar will remain in the government and 
reforms will continue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

