<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Complete Surprise' to Fedorov </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1601164494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1503 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1601164494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Finance Minister, Boris Fedorov, told 
Interfax on Sunday [16 January] that Yegor Gaydar's statement 
that he will not join the reorganized government was a "complete 
surprise" to him. 
  Fedorov himself declined to give any information concerning 
his own plans. 
  It's not clear whether Fedorov will join the number of the 
new deputy premiers or remain as finance minister. 
  In the meantime Interfax learned from Russia's prominent 
banking circles that for them Fedorov symbolizes reforms in 
Russia, and that his withdrawal from the highest government 
echelons may come to be viewed as a symptom of the possibility 
that the direction of economic reforms in Russia might change. 

</TEXT>

