<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Other Officials View Resignation of Gaydar </TI></H3>
<H4>   Poltoranin Assesses Resignations </H4>
<F P=102> LD1701165194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1501 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1701165194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mikhail Poltoranin, a member of the Russia's Choice 
parliamentary faction, told INTERFAX on Monday [17 January] that 
Viktor Chernomyrdin expected Yegor Gaydar to reject the post of 
first deputy premier, and "probably did all he could to make 
this happen." 
  Poltoranin disagreed with the notion that Russia's Choice 
used Gaydar's and Pamfilova's resignations to distance itself 
from the president. "We do not want it, and we hope that the 
president will not deviate from democratic principles. Then we 
will be with him," he said. 
  Poltoranin qualified Gaydar's and Pamfilova's resignations 
as 
"a logical step stemming from the policy pursued by the 
Chernomyrdin group in the government." 
  "It was a well-considered, not an impulsive, step, since the 
outlooks of Chernomyrdin and Gaydar differ greatly. Gaydar and 
the entire group of reformers have no right to serve as a cover 
for the degradation of the economy and management system. 
Gaydar's withdrawal is bad for Russia, but there is no other 
way out," Poltoranin stressed. 
  Russia's Choice, he added, analyzed the situation earlier, 
and suggested a month before December's elections that Gaydar 
should resign and distance himself from the government "to stop 
being in the shadow of errors the government committed in 1993." 
  "At that time this decision was not endorsed, since we did 
not want to introduce an element of destabilization in society 
and lose the new Constitution, because many people could decide 
not to vote because of it," Poltoranin said. "Today this factor 
no longer exists, and so we can make decisions more openly." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

