<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Other Officials View Resignation of Gaydar </TI></H3>
<H4>   Baburin Comments </H4>
<F P=102> LD1701164994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1501 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1701164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yegor Gaydar's refusal to accept the post of first 
deputy premier is "a step in his game against the government," 
said a member of the State Duma, Sergey Baburin, who leads the 
Russian People's Union. According to him, in the present 
circumstances "Viktor Chernomyrdin will have to justify himself 
and defend what Gaydar did over the past two years." 
  In Baburin's opinion, expressed in an interview with 
Interfax 
on Monday, Gaydar's step was prompted by Russia's Choice in view 
of the 1996 presidential elections, "in order to distance 
themselves from the current economic situation, lay all the 
blame on Chernomyrdin and his technocrats, and force the entire 
opposition to start defending Russia's government in connection 
with Russia's Choice's attack on it." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

