<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says Gaydar `Incompetent' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801104294 Tehran IRNA in English 1026 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801104294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, Jan. 18, IRNA -- Several Russian 
parliamentarians have termed acceptance of the resignation of 
first deputy prime minister Yegor Gaydar by President Boris 
Yeltsin as a political maneuver and accused Gaydar of being 
incompetent in the administration of affairs. Russian economist 
Grigoriy Yavlinskiy who is said to succeed Gaydar, in an 
interview with IRNA here Monday described Gaydar as an 
incompetent person for membership in the new cabinet. 
  He said that Gaydar always introduced the former speaker of 
parliament Ruslan Khasbulatov as the main obstacle on the way of 
economic reforms but during the past three months since the 
dissolution of the parliament he did not carry out any 
constructive measure. 
  Comparing certain members of the government with that of the 
former Soviet Union, he claimed that some of them only thought 
about having fashionable offices, modern cars and luxury houses 
instead of paying attention to more important matters. He 
reiterated that he would not accept the post of deputy prime 
minister. 

</TEXT>

