<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Choice Officials React to Gaydar Resignation </TI></H3>
<H4>   Secretary Yushenkov Comments </H4>
<F P=102> LD1601185294 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1700 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1601185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] A meeting of the bureau of the parliamentary faction 
of the Russia's Choice bloc was held this morning. Sergey 
Yushenkov, secretary of the faction, said that members of the 
bureau unanimously backed Yegor Gaydar's decision to resign from 
the post of first deputy prime minister. Yushenkov also said 
that Minister of Finance Boris Fedorov also intends to leave the 
government because, like Gaydar, he is unable to bear 
responsibility for a policy that will inevitably result in a new 
spiral of inflation. However, Boris Fedorov himself has so far 
declined to give any information about his own plans. He said 
that Yegor Gaydar's statement on his refusal to join the 
government came as a complete surprise to him. 
  Meanwhile, leading Russian banking circles have told 
Interfax 
that they regard Boris Fedorov as a symbol of reform in Russia 
and that they might perceive his departure from the top echelons 
of the government as symptomatic of a possible change in the 
direction of the reforms. 
  At his press conference, Yegor Gaydar stated that Viktor 
Chernomyrdin had asked him during their conversation about his 
view of the possible appointment of Grigoriy Yavlinskiy to the 
post of first deputy prime minister in the new government. 
Gaydar said that he would warmly support his candidacy. As for 
Yavlinskiy, the leader of the Yabloko parliamentary bloc, he 
told the Interfax agency that no one has offered him a place in 
the Russian Government. Asked whether he would accept such an 
offer were it to be forthcoming, Yavlinsky replied: Most 
probably not, but all the same it is too soon to say. Moreover, 
an offer to join the government in the post of first deputy 
prime minister has to come from the president, and I have my 
doubts as to whether I could work with Boris Yeltsin, Yavlinskiy 
stressed. 

</TEXT>

