<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Choice Officials React to Gaydar Resignation </TI></H3>
<H4>   More Russia's Choice Comment </H4>
<F P=102> LD1701170094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1501 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1701170094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] "Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin's decision to 
form a new government without Yegor Gaydar is, I feel, final, as 
is the prime minister's decision to weaken the economic reform 
thrust," Sergey Kovalyov, one of the leaders of the Russia's 
Choice group in the State Duma, told INTERFAX. In his view, 
this decision "is likely to bring about serious negative 
consequences." 
  Kovalyov emphasized that it had been a mistake to regard 
Russia's Choice as the government party. 
  "I kept repeating in every speech I made that we could not 
be 
a government party without having a decisive influence in the 
government," he said. 
  The Russia's Choice group intended to nominate Mikhail 
Mityukov to the position of deputy speaker. In his words, the 
group will not let Liberal Democratic Party [LDPR] leader 
Vladimir Zhirinovskiy chair the International Affairs Committee. 
  "We will vote against this, and democratically-minded 
deputies have enough votes to make this impossible. What is 
more, I suspect that the communists also do not intend to let 
the LDPR have that position," Kovalyov explained. 
  He said that his group will support election of either 
Vladimir Lukin of the Yavlinskiy-Boldyrev-Lukin bloc or former 
first deputy foreign minister Anatoliy Adamishin to that 
position. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

