<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Liberal Democratic Party Welcomes Resignation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1601192094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1825 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1601192094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Liberal Democratic Party will welcome Yegor 
Gaydar's decision to resign, this party's first vice chairman 
and State Duma deputy Stanislav Zhebrovsky told Interfax. 
  He believes, however, that "one private move does not 
determine everything." Besides Gaydar and Ella Pamfilova, the 
government must be quit by vice premiers Anatoly Chubays and 
Boris Fedorov, because "they are responsible for the country's 
ruin." 
  Zhebrovsky is convinced that resignation under such a far- 
fetched pretext as disagreement with the decision to allocate 
$500 Mn to the construction of a parliamentary center and to 
unite the Russian and Belarusian monetary systems" attests to 
the bankruptcy of the current policy. He thinks that for the 
Russian economy $500 Mn is not the sum that determines success 
or failure of a government program. 

</TEXT>

