<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Business Circles Concerned Over Resignation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701113494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1127 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1701113494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 17 TASS -- "By announcing his 
resignation, Yegor Gaydar set the Russian president before the 
alternative: Either to go on with the reform policy, or to allow 
the government to be controlled by those officials who are 
backed by directors of ineffective economy," Chairman of the 
Economic Freedom Party Konstantin Borovoy told ITAR-TASS. 
  Other business people told ITAR-TASS about their anxiety 
over 
the growing instability on the Russian market, which will 
inevitably follow the resignation of Yegor Gaydar from the post 
of first deputy prime minister. 
  In the opinion of Mikhail Dunin, vice president of the 
Moscow 
Commodity Exchange, "Gaydar's resignation will trigger panic at 
commodity and stock exchanges, as a result of which the dollar 
exchange rate may reach 1,500 - 1,600 roubles before the end of 
January." The growth of the dollar exchange rate will 
"automatically lead to another round of inflation, to the growth 
of prices, including hard currency prices." Dunin stated with 
regret that "hopes for the stabilisation of the situation on the 
Russian market, that emerged after December 12, are not coming 
true, which may enhance the prestige of Zhirinovskiy." Aside 
from it Dunin, the same as other business people, complained 
that "endless cataclysms in the Russian Government do not allow 
business people to implement long-term programmes, because the 
unpredictable character of the policy, pursued by the Cabinet of 
Ministers, does not make it possible to forecast the situation 
on the Russian market." 
  Oleg Vinogradov, chairman of the board of directors of the 
Mosexpo joint-stock company, regards Gaydar's announcement of 
his resignation as an "untimely step". He accused the first 
deputy prime minister of giving up the attempts to form a 
government, which would guarantee the continuation of the 
reform." 
  Sergey Popov, adviser to the president of the Association of 
Russian Banks, has an opinion of his own about Gaydar's 
statement. He believes that Grigoriy Yavlinskiy, a possible 
successor of Gaydar on the post of first deputy prime minister, 
"is more adequate to Russian realities." Popov likes 
Yavlinskiy's desire to get from the prime minister the 
guarantees of the implementation of a clear programme of actions 
and to take upon himself the responsibility for the reform 
course. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

