<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bankers View Resignation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701165694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1501 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1701165694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Gaydar's resignation may alleviate the confrontation 
between those in the government who favor tough and fast 
reforms, and those who prefer gradual ones, the Deputy Chairman 
of Incombank's council of experts, Sergey Popov, told INTERFAX. 
  According to Popov, the possibility that Fedorov may resign 
after Gaydar and Pamfilov did "will not lead to a crisis in the 
government." He views Yavlinskiy as the most acceptable 
candidate for the post of finance minister. 
  The Director of the foreign relations department of 
Stolichny 
Bank, Aleksnder Skvortsov, said he hopes that Gaydar's 
resignation will not be accepted. According to him, only Gaydar 
can conclude the reforms launched in Russia. 
  The Deputy Chairman of NGS Bank, Viktor Shabrov, said that 
"the policy of reforms is not carried out by one man; the 
question is who will replace him." 
  A majority of spokesmen for commercial banks do not link the 
fall of the ruble with the government reshuffling, since Fedorov 
envisaged it at the end of last year. However, the rate of the 
fall heightened "because of instability in the highest echelons 
of power." 

</TEXT>

