</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zlenko: Accord `Not Subject' to Ratification </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1601213794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1828 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1601213794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Speaking on national TV, Ukraine's Foreign Minister, 
Anatoliy Zlenko, said that "the document signed in Moscow is not 
subject to ratification by Ukraine's parliament." Under the 
bill on international agreements adopted by Ukraine's parliament 
recently, such statements are not subject to the process of 
ratification, he pointed out. The document signed by the 
Russian, American and Ukrainian presidents in Moscow "serves to 
develop the resolution on the ratification of START-1 adopted by 
the Ukrainian parliament, Zlenko said. 
  According to him, no nuclear country recognized the way 
Ukraine's parliament ratified START-1. "International isolation 
could bring Ukraine to its knees. Its independence would be out 
of the question," the foreign minister said. 
  Earlier a number of influential members of Ukraine's 
parliament strongly criticized the trilateral document on 
Ukraine's nuclear disarmament signed in Moscow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

