<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   On Moscow's Refusal To Wipe Out Debt </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401173994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1453 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401173994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko has 
expressed surprise and disagreement with his Russian counterpart 
Andrey Kozyrev's statement saying Moscow will not write off 
Kiev's debt for fuel imports from Russia as compensation for the 
withdrawal of the nuclear weapons Ukraine had inherited from 
ex-USSR. He spoke in an interview with Interfax on Friday. 
  Ukraine's debt for fuel imports from Russia ran at more than 
1 Tn rubles as of December 1, 1993, according to Russia's 
government statistical committee. 
  Earlier in the day, Kozyrev told Interfax that Kiev would 
receive fuel grade uranium for its nuclear reactors but "any 
write-off of the Ukrainian debt is out of the question." 
  For his own part, President Kravchuk, speaking at a news 
conference in the Ukrainian embassy on Friday, said Moscow was 
committed to compensating Ukraine both for long range and 
tactical nuclear weapons. 
  Kravchuk said Ukraine is to receive compensation in fuel 
grade uranium for the withdrawal of the long range weapons from 
its territory but Moscow will be solely in charge of exports of 
500 tons of the uranium reprocessed from the nuclear warheads. 
  The Ukrainian leader said experts on the three sides were 
yet 
to define the amount and form of compensation for the tactical 
nuclear weapons to be withdrawn from Ukraine. He believes one 
option is to write off Kiev's debt for fuel imports from Russia. 
  As he rejected Kozyrev's statement, the Ukrainian minister 
said the write off formula was laid down in the tripartite 
agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

