<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament To Discuss Accord `Next Week' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1601195294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1741 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1601195294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoly Gordeyev] </F>
  [Text] Kiev January 16 TASS -- Ukraine's political and 
public forces are not unanimous in assessing the results of the 
U.S.- Russian-Ukrainian summit in Moscow. 
  The Ukrainian parliament expects to discuss next week the 
agreement signed at the tripartite meeting. However, some 
opposition deputies, largely representing parties and movements 
of radical nationalist orientation, have already denounced the 
agreement reached by the three presidents and labelled the 
results of the Moscow meeting as "betrayal of independent 
Ukraine's interests." 
  Yuriy Kosenko, head of Ukraine's parliamentary commission 
for 
nuclear disarmament, also gave his view on the matter speaking 
on Sunday in the radio programme "Ukraine and the World." He 
said he would like to read the texts of the documents before 
coming up with any legal conclusions about their lawfulness or 
unlawfulness. This view was supported by Anton Buteyko, chief 
of the presidential international service, who spoke in the same 
programme. He emphasised that some ukrainian leaders had 
rejected the document they had never seen, since it was of a 
purely confidential character. 
  Ukrainian Defence Minister Vitaly Radetskyy told reporters 
that the main issue to be addressed at present was deactivation 
of the nuclear weapons, which calls for immediate solution 
because the time of warheads safe keeping was expiring. 
According to Radetskyy, nuclear disarmament is not to affect in 
any way the level of defence capability of the Ukrainian armed 
forces. Moreover, security guarantees and Ukraine's territorial 
integrity and independence which to be ensured by the leading 
nuclear powers are designed to guarantee the republic's economic 
revival and integration into the European and World markets, as 
well as its recognition as an equal partner in cooperation for 
peace. 

</TEXT>

