<H3> <TI>   Deputy Sets Conditions for Ratification </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401181294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1453 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401181294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Deputy head of the Parliamentary Foreign Affairs 
Commission Yevgeniy Marmazov says the tripartite nuclear 
disarmament agreement signed in Moscow will be considered by the 
incumbent parliament because a new one will not be able to 
convene until May. 
  In an interview with Interfax-Ukraine, Marmazov said the 
Supreme Soviet would not ratify the deal unless the conditions 
it had set for the ratification of the Start-I treaty were met. 
  Last November, the Supreme Soviet ratified the Start-I 
agreement but with some strings attached. Among other things, 
the deputies demanded security guarantees and sufficient 
compensation for the nuclear weapons Ukraine had inherited from 
the former Soviet Union. 
  Under the parliament-approved deal, Kiev is to transfer 36 
percent of its long range missiles and 42 percent of the nuclear 
warheads to Russia. 

</TEXT>

