<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deal `Not Likely' To Be Implemented </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1601172694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1503 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1601172694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Moscow deal on the withdrawal of nuclear weapons 
from Ukrainian soil is part of "President Kravchuk's defeatist 
policy," member of the parliamentary commission for defence and 
security matters Igor Derkach told Interfax on Saturday. 
  He says the agreement is not likely to be implemented given 
further economic recession in Ukraine. 
  Derkach pointed to a lack of convincing arguments in 
statements by the American and Russian leaders about security 
guarantees and technical assistance to Ukraine. "The $175 Mn 
aid to Ukraine the Americans promised a long time ago will be 
used to pay U.S. experts," he said. 
  The dismantling and transfer of long-range missiles from 
Ukraine to Russia will cost $3 Bn, according to the estimates 
local experts made prior to the ratification of the Start I 
agreement by Ukrainian deputies. 

</TEXT>

