<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lvov Council Head Airs Doubts on Nuclear Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1501173394 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 0820 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1501173394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lvov -- Mykola Horyn, Lvov Oblast council chairman 
and a candidate for people's deputy of Ukraine, said in a 
conversation with a UNIAN correspondent on 14 January that his 
stance regarding nuclear weapons differs from the stance of his 
brothers -- Mykhaylo Horyn, chairman of the Ukrainian Republican 
Party, and Bohdan Horyn, people's deputy of Ukraine, who are in 
favor of keeping nuclear weapons on our territory. Mykola Horyn 
proposed an approach to this issue not from a political, but 
from a technical and economic aspect, for nuclear weapons have 
not only to be stored, but properly serviced too. 
  "These weapons have to be tested. But will Lvov and other 
oblast councils give permission for underground nuclear 
explosion tests to be conducted on their territories?" Mykola 
Horyn posed the question. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

