<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Results, Reaction to Crimean Elections Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Bahrov, Meshkov To Face Runoff </H4>
<F P=102> WS1701102094 Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network in 
Ukrainian 0600 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1701102094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Our listeners are greatly interested in the results 
of the 16 January presidential election in the Crimea. 
According to reports from our Simferopol correspondent, out of 
the six candidates running, no one received the required number 
of votes for an outright victory. Viktor (Alsufiev), chairman 
of the Central Electoral Commission, said that the commission 
will have to discuss a runoff between the two candidates 
receiving the most votes in yesterday's election. Yuriy 
Meshkov, leader of the Republican Party of the Crimea, came in 
first in both Simferopol and Sevastopol, as well as in many 
rural areas. Yuriy Meshkov received 540,000 votes altogether. 
The second-place candidate for the presidential office is 
Mykola Bahrov -- chairman of the Crimean Supreme Soviet -- who 
received 245,000 votes. Third place is occupied by Serhey 
Shuvaynikov, of the Russian Party of the Crimea, who won 186,000 
votes. Leonid Hrach, leader of Crimean communists, received 
some 180,000 votes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

