<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Results, Reaction to Crimean Elections Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Returns Being Examined </H4>
<F P=102> LD1701193294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1807 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1701193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The head of the presidential public relations 
office, Nikolay Mikhalchenko, told INTERFAX-Ukraine today that 
"the returns of the recent elections in the Crimea were being 
examined." He added that "specific decisions will be made in 
accordance with the Constitution of Ukraine" in the near future. 
  Mikhalchenko pointed out that the Ukrainian Constitution 
never envisioned presidential elections in the Crimea. He also 
said Ukrainian Speaker Ivan Plyushch had warned the Crimean 
parliament of the impossibility of holding such elections before. 
  The Ukrainian president's press office is expected to come 
out with a statement on the issue in a day or two. 
  As a result of the first round of the presidential elections 
in the Crimea on January 16, the leader of the Republican Party 
of the Crimea, Yuriy Meshkov, led the race with 38.8 percent of 
the electorate. He is widely known as a supporter of the 
Crimea's unification with Russia. 
  Ukrainian patriotic forces will never recognize the legality 
of the presidential elections in the Crimea, according to the 
statement the leader of the Civic Congress of the Crimea, Sergey 
Litvinov, made in an interview with INTERFAX-Ukraine. 
  At the same time, he admitted that the Crimean elections 
were 
a fiasco of nationalist movements whose popularity on the 
peninsula is very low. 
  In his opinion, this is a result of the Ukrainian 
leadership's imprudent policy which left Crimean Ukrainians with 
no support. 
  A deputy of the Ukrainian parliament and one of the leaders 
of the nationalist movement "Rukh," Les Tanyuk, commented on 
the election returns by saying that their main result was the 
failure of Kravchuk's team. 
  "People voted not against Nikolay Bahrov (Speaker of the 
Ukrainian parliament -- INTERFAX) as a politician, but rather 
against Bahrov as Kravchuk's representative," he told 
INTERFAX-Ukraine. 
  He put all the blame for this on the Ukrainian president who 
failed to promptly stand up against the illegal elections as a 
guarantor of the Constitution. 
  Tanyuk said Yuriy Meshkov promised easy ways out of simple 
situations and in this sense he was one of Zhirinovskiy's men to 
a great extent. 
  The repercussions of the elections may be very dangerous and 
disastrous both for Ukraine and Russia, as well as for the whole 
of Europe, Tanyuk said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-56500 </DOCNO>
