<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Decree Orders Reshuffle of Security Agencies </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1501123994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1228 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1501123994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tigran Liloyan] </F>
  [Text] Yerevan security agencies will be reshuffled to 
better respond to their new goals, having emerged since Armenia 
acquired independence. These goals radically differ from those 
pursued in the totalitarian period, according to a decree by 
Armenian President Levon Ter-Petrosyan, released here today. 
  The decree liquidates the so-called "operational services" 
of 
Armenia's State Office for National Security which were formerly 
engaged in ideological control over the population. Their staff 
will be paid salaries during next three months, after which 
period they will either be fired or fill other positions in the 
state office departments, according to results of professional 
fitness tests. All security personnel are subject to these 
tests, the decree says. 
  New guidelines for the State Office for National Security 
will be developed, along with a new structure of the agency. 
  Under the decree, the main border-guard administration, 
agencies in charge of guarding strategically important 
enterprises, financial and medical departments of the state 
security office, as well as its technical maintenance services 
will keep functioning until the complete restructuring will take 
place. Possibly, they will form the foundation for Armenia's 
future security service. 
  David Shakhnazaryan, 39, who since March 1993 was an 
ambassador at large under the Armenian president, has been 
appointed an acting head of the State Office for National 
Security. He is to replace Eduard Simonyants, who headed the 
office since February 1993 and now will fill another post. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

