<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iranian Official on Joint Initiative on Karabakh </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1701194694 Yerevan Radio Yerevan International Service in 
Armenian 2000 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1701194694 </F>
<F P=104>  Yerevan Radio Yerevan International Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Armenian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Morteza Bank, head of the Eastern Europe and CIS 
Department at the Iranian Foreign Ministry, said in a news 
conference at the Iranian Embassy on 13 January that the 
developments taking place in the region naturally have a serious 
affect on the relations between our two countries. The search 
for ways to settle the Karabakh problem, which is one of the 
important regional problems, is the reason for my visit to 
Armenia, Bank said. 
  Asked by an ARMENPRES correspondent if a new Iranian-Russian 
mediation initiative could be expected following his visit that 
came in the aftermath of the recent visit to Iran and Azerbaijan 
by Russian Special Ambassador Kazimirov, Morteza Bank said: 
Naturally, the countries in the region could play a big part in 
the solution of that problem. Iran and Russia, which are the 
largest countries in the region, could engage in effective 
activity both with a separate and a joint initiative. Mr. 
Kazimirov's visit pursued such an aim. We have agreed to 
cooperate and positive developments have already taken place. 
Of course, this does not mean that our activity would not be 
coordinated with the efforts of the CSCE. I think that there 
are reasons for optimism that the will to attain peace is 
gaining ground. 
  In touching upon Armenian-Iranian economic and cultural 
relations, Bank noted that they are underlined by the principles 
and traditions of mutual interest, good-neigborliness, and 
centuries old friendship between the two countries, and these 
ties should develop normally. 

</TEXT>

