<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Split' Over Karabakh Recognition Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1701141594 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 15 Jan 94 First 
Edition p 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM1701141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Sergey Bablumyan: "Split in Yerevan Over Whether </F>
Or Not To Recognize Nagorno-Karabakh Republic"] 
  [Text] Yerevan -- People in Armenia want peace for the 
people of Karabakh and for themselves, a peace worthy of the 
losses sustained and the suffering endured. Translated into the 
language of specific action, this means an immediate cease-fire 
without prior conditions, guaranteeing the safety of the 
civilian population of Nagorno-Karabakh, and deciding at the 
negotiating table who is to repay debts, to whom, how much, and 
how. 
  President Levon Ter-Petrosyan is right to believe that he 
has 
the support of all Armenia on this issue. The republic, cut off 
from the outside world by a long-standing blockade, is barely 
able to keep its economy afloat. The war in Karabakh has in one 
way or another affected the well-being of every Armenian family, 
and people realize that it cannot go on endlessly. 
  "We have managed to strike off the agenda the status of 
Nagorno-Karabakh and focus entirely on the main problem: How 
can peace be achieved?", Aram Abramyan, the Armenian president's 
press secretary, told IZVESTIYA. "The two ways proposed by the 
CSCE and Russia are equally acceptable to us. The advantage of 
the Russian scenario is that it contains a specific mechanism to 
prevent the resumption of hostilities -- to whit, the 
introduction of internationally-mandated peacekeeping forces 
into the conflict zone. Both plans of action proposed to the 
warring parties have won the approval of Stepanakert and 
Yerevan, but they were rejected by Azerbaijan. The conflict in 
Nagorno-Karabakh has today reached the stage where its peaceful 
resolution depends not only on the will of the warring parties, 
but also on that of the world community." 
  Armenia's political parties are unhappy that Yerevan has not 
made up its mind to recognize the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic 
[NKR]. Armenia's influential "Ramkavar-Azatakan" 
Liberal-Democratic Party is in favor of recognizing the NKR as 
an independent sovereign state. In the opinion of party leader 
Ruben Mirzakhanyan, this step would make it possible to unravel 
one of the tightest knots of the conflict. It is a question of 
the decision of the then Armenian SSR [Soviet Socialist 
Republic] Supreme Soviet of 1 December 1989 declaring 
Nagorno-Karabakh Autonomous Oblast [NKAO] an inalienable part of 
Armenia. 
  It was clear at the time that this decision was as futile as 
the Azerbaijani authorities' ensuing decision to dissolve the 
NKAO. However, having effectively changed nothing, both 
documents are still formally in force to this day. Yerevan's 
official recognition of the NKR would, in Ruben Mirzkhanyan's 
opinion, remove the problem. 
  "We do not believe that the process of settling the conflict 
is becoming more productive as the group of international 
mediators expands," he said. In his opinion, this group should 
be confined to the warring parties' immediate neighbors -- 
Turkey, Iran, and, undoubtedly, Russia. 
  "We have very serious disagreements with the authorities in 
our approach to the Nagorno-Karabakh problem," Vagan Oganesyan, 
one of the leaders of the "Dashnaktsutyun" opposition party, 
told IZVESTIYA. "We cannot in particular see whether we are 
complying with the Supreme Soviet decision for Nagorno-Karabakh 
to accede to Armenia or whether we agree with its proclaiming 
itself the NKR? If Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh are in actual 
fact a single state, Azerbaijan is in effect at war with 
Armenia, whereas the latter does not acknowledge itself to be a 
state at war. "If we consider the NKR a separate state 
formation, why do we not recognize the republic de jure?" 
[quotation marks as published] Vagan Oganesyan wonders. 
  Vagan Oganesyan believes that Russia will play a crucial 
role 
in resolving the conflict and its participation in these affairs 
is therefore far more preferable to mediation by any other 
country or international organization. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

