Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on New Appointments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1701152194 Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN in English 0811 GMT 
17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1701152194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From 17 January PAEVALEHT, p 3] </F>
  [Excerpt] Monday, January 17 -- New Foreign Minister Juri 
Luik said that he accepted the offer of the ministerial post 
since he already had some experience in foreign politics. He 
had also stressed the political aspect in his work as the 
defence minister, Luik added. 
  Luik commended the intellectual potential of the Foreign 
Ministry and hoped that he could exploit it efficiently. He 
also expressed his confidence that the new Defence Minister 
Indrek Kannik will manage well. 
  The main guarantee of Estonia's statehood is its impeccable 
reputation and other countries' awareness of Estonia, Luik went 
on. It is extremely difficult to interfere in the politics of a 
peaceful and stable country and there are few states ready for 
an outright aggression, he stressed. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

