<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Request To Join `Partnership for Peace' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1401202994 Tallinn BNS in English 1603 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1401202994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 14, BNS -- Estonian President Lennart 
Meri and Prime Minister Mart Laar today signed a letter to NATO 
Secretary-General Manfred Woerner informing him of Estonia's 
wish to join the Partnership for Peace program. 
  Meri said after the signing this is "a historic decision 
that 
will have a stabilizing effect not only on Estonia but on the 
entire northern Europe, and which concerns all Estonia's 
neighbors." In the president's view, neither a system of 
agreements nor a well-equipped army offer the most reliable 
guarantees of peace, but a democratic system of government. 
"Democratic states never pose a danger to each other," he said. 
  "Partnership for Peace was the best NATO could at present 
offer to East European states," Meri said. Commenting on 
Lithuanian President Algirdas Brazauskas' bid for full NATO 
membership, Meri said Estonia and Lithuania face different 
problems, and that there are no foreign troops in Lithuania nor 
territorial issues that need solving. 
  Laar said Lithuania did not inform the Estonian Government 
of 
its request for NATO membership alluding to problems arising 
from the differences between the Estonian and the Lithuanian 
Constitutions. He affirmed, however, that the meetings of the 
three states' premiers have repeatedly touched on Baltic 
cooperation in the framework of the Partnership for Peace 
program. The Estonian premier cited the setting up of the Baltic 
peacekeeping battalion as a concrete step in this direction. 
  Asked whether the joint signing of the letter today 
signifies 
"domestic peace" between the president and the prime minister, 
Meri said, "The joint signing of this document should rule out 
such rhetorical questions being asked here today." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

