<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Negotiator to Talks With Russia Views Delay </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1801092194 Tallinn BNS in English 1828 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1801092194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 17, BNS -- Estonia agrees in principle 
to Russia's proposal to withdraw its troops from Estonia by Aug. 
31, but expects Russia to present a detailed withdrawal 
timetable in the next round of talks, Vaino Reinart, Estonia's 
top negotiator at talks with Russia, told BNS. 
  "When we get the timetable, we can say whether we agree to 
it 
or not," he said. "But, it shouldn't affect the final deadline 
of troop pullout, which we are in principle prepared to accept." 
  The head of the Estonian delegation noted that Estonia's 
chief requirement is that Russian combat units should leave 
Tallinn. 
  The next round of Estonian-Russian negotiations was 
scheduled 
to begin tomorrow near Moscow, but it was postponed due to 
Russia's top negotiator Vasili Svirin's sickness. Reinart said 
the new date will be set within a week. 
  Reinart affirmed that his appointment as head of the 
Estonian 
delegation is not going to change the delegation's work. 
  "The general direction of the talks is anyway set by the 
foreign minister, and we work closely together with (Estonian 
Foreign Minister) Juri Luik," Reinart told BNS. 
  Reinart was appointed head of the Estonian delegation last 
week. He succeeded former Defense Minister Juri Luik, who was 
appointed Foreign Minister. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

