<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ulmanis' `Bewilderment' Over Clinton Remarks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701210394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1956 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1701210394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis has expressed on 
Monday a bewilderment in connection with the pronouncements on 
the problem of human rights in Latvia and Estonia made by the 
U.S. President Bill Clinton during his visit to Moscow. 
  "There are no violations of human rights of the sort which 
was alleged to", the Latvian president stressed at the briefing 
devoted to a regular meeting of the Council of National Security 
of the republic. 
  The results of the meeting of the U.S. and Russian 
presidents 
and the Partnership for Peace program in the NATO framework were 
discussed at the meeting. 
  "I cannot believe that the two superpowers have finally 
decided the fate of small countries" said G. Ulmanis answering 
the questions about the attitude to the references of B. Clinton 
and B. Yeltsin to the Baltic states, in particular to the 
dependence of the schedule of withdrawal of Russian troops from 
Latvia and Estonia on the solution of the human rights problem. 
  The president thinks that "a law on citizenship must be 
passed as soon as possible in Latvia which would exclude any 
speculations on the subject of human rights". Ulmanis said that 
he was expecting information from the Russian and American sides 
on the final deadline of withdrawal of Russian troops from 
Latvia and Estonia and on the conditions of keeping a Russian 
radar station on the territory of Latvia. 
  In the nearest future, said Ulmanis, Latvia will send a 
letter to the NATO leadership with agreement to participate in 
the Partnership for Progress [as received] in accordance with a 
decision taken at the Council of National Security meeting. 
  The president emphasized that in view of joining the 
Partnership for Progress, where Russia will also participate, 
Latvia must "carefully review its relations with Russia". 
  G. Ulmanis also said that the Latvia's joining of NATO is "a 
remote prospect". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

