<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on President's Reaction </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1801090094 Tallinn BNS in English 1828 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1801090094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Jan 17, BNS -- The U.S.-Russian presidential 
summit could help adjust talks between Latvia and Russia on the 
terms of dismantling the Skrunda radar and the deadline for the 
Russian troops' withdrawal, Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis 
told reporters Monday. 
  The meeting between the presidents Boris Yeltsin and Bill 
Clinton could make Russia more compliant in talks with Latvia, 
said a NATO representative in another press conference today in 
Riga. 
  Commenting on the issue of human rights, Ulmanis said he was 
"surprised" by the allegations of human rights restrictions in 
Latvia, voiced during the Moscow summit. 
  Latvia needs to prompt the adoption of a citizenship law to 
stop "philosophizing over these topics," the president said. The 
National Security Council also supports the stance, said Ulmanis. 
  Ulmanis has not received official information on the Moscow 
summit yet, he said. 

</TEXT>

