<F P=100> Turkmenistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Niyazov Wins Further Term After Referendum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1501190494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1457 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1501190494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A national referendum is under way in Turkmenistan 
to reveal the public view on the parliament's recent decision to 
keep the incumbent president Saparmurad Niyazov for the second 
five-year term without elections. 
  As the Vice-Chairman of the Central Electoral Commission in 
Turkmenistan Alexander Dodonov has told Interfax, the referendum 
can be regarded as valid since by 10:00 local time more than 
76% of the electorate cast their ballots. By preliminary 
returns from the commission, of the 1.95 Mn registered 
constituents, 1.93 Mn (98.9%) voted by noon local time. 
  Although the final returns won't be known until Sunday's 
morning, even today it's clear that President Niyazov will stay 
in office for the next five years. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

