<H3> <TI>   Cooperation Documents Signed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1501151194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1449 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1501151194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By BELINFORM correspondent for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Minsk January 15 TASS -- A memorandum on mutual 
understanding, which expresses the intention to create a 
Belarusian-U.S. commission on agricultural businesses and 
development of rural areas was signed here today during the 
Minsk stay of U.S. President Bill Clinton. The U.S. President 
voiced the availability of additional credits for Belarusian 
purchases of U.S. foodstuffs. 
  Shushkevich and Clinton are satisfied with a bilateral 
agreement on science and technology which provides for quick 
expansion of scientific information exchange and joint R&amp;D. 
  An agreement to continue the elaboration of documents 
against 
double taxation and on cooperation in peaceful uses of nuclear 
energy has been reached as well. 
  Bill Clinton told the Belarusian leader they will pass over 
to Belarus ten million dollars worth of medical equipment. 
  The sides discussed prospects for democratic reforms in 
Belarus and parliamentary elections. Clinton expressed the hope 
the elections will be held in 1994 and promised technical 
assistance to their organization. 
  The leaders voiced their support to international efforts 
for 
settlement of international conflicts, consolidation of 
independence, sovereignty and territorial integrity of all 
states, including new independent nations of the former Soviet 
Union. 
  The Belarusian parliament speaker and the U.S. President 
noted recent progress in overcoming the division of the European 
continent and outlining ways towards more close cooperation 
between states. President Clinton dwelt on his initiative 
Partnership for Peace, and Shushkevich assured the President 
Belarus will thoroughly analyze a possibility of their 
participation in the initiative. 
  Shushkevich and Clinton expressed common opinion the 
Belarusian visit of the U.S. President made a weighty 
contribution to consolidation of bilateral friendship, 
cooperation and mutual understanding. 
  President Clinton expressed profound gratitude to the 
Belarusian Supreme Soviet, government and people for warm 
reception of his family, the U.S. delegation and himself. 

</TEXT>

