<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton on Russia's Role in `Partnership for Peace' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401180494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1642 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401180494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Aleksey Agureyev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 14 TASS -- "Russian can play a 
critical role (in "Partnership for Peace")," President Clinton 
said in an exclusive interview with ITAR-TASS on Friday [14 
January]. He was speaking straight after addressing the Russian 
people from the Ostankino Television studios. 
  Clinton said Russia could do its part "in two ways - first 
of 
all, the Russian military are still one of the best trained and 
best armed militaries in the world. So, for Russia and the 
United States to participate means all these other military 
armies, particularly from the smaller countries, get a chance to 
do planning, and training, and actual exercises at a much higher 
level, than they would otherwise. 
  "In other words, it's a big thing. It increases the capacity 
of their armed forces and their sense of security. 
  "Also, if Russia joins the "Partnership for Peace", one of 
the conditions for joining is saying, "We promise to be good 
neighbors. We respect the terrritorial boundaries of all the 
other countries in the "Partnership for Peace". So it takes 
away one of the big fears that you hear in some countries or in 
the Baltics or wherever. [no end quotation mark as received] 
  Responding to a question about what impressions of Russia he 
will take home, the President said, "I think it's a wonderful 
country and I have had a wonderful trip. And I think you're 
going to have a great future. I know this is a tough time, but 
you'll work through it. You'll figure it out." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

