<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Other Officials View Resignation of Gaydar </TI></H3>
<H4>   Sergeyev Comments </H4>
<F P=102> LD1601164294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1503 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1601164294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In answer to Interfax's question concerning Prime 
Minister Chernomyrdin's reaction to Gaydar's decision, the 
leader of the government's press service, Valentin Sergeyev, 
said that it was "calm". According to him, the first deputy 
premier's decision not to join the reorganized government was 
not unexpected. 
  "Evidently it's extremely hard, and maybe politically 
illogical, to be the leader of a parliamentary faction and serve 
as first deputy prime minister at the same time," Sergeyev said. 
"The issue of whether Gaydar should be the leader of 
parliamentary faction or first deputy premier has been raised 
more than once, and now Gaydar made his choice." 
  Chernomyrdin did nothing to nudge Gaydar toward taking this 
decision, Sergeyev stressed, because Gaydar was appointed first 
deputy premier several months ago at Chernomyrdin's initiative. 
  As Sergeyev said, Gaydar's leaving the government will not 
alter the policy of reforms pursued by the Cabinet led by 
Chernomyrdin. 
  "The government has been, and will be, reformist. The course 
of reforms underlies the government's program for 1994- 1995 
approved by President Yeltsin," he said. 
  In answer to Interfax's question as to who may replace 
Gaydar 
in the government, Sergeyev said with reference to Viktor 
Chernomyrdin that "this complicated question will be resolved by 
the president together with the government's leadership". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

