</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Holds News Conference on Return From Moscow </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1501143094 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
1720 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1501143094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [News conference by President Leonid Kravchuk with </F>
unidentified reporters at Borispil Airport in Kiev on 14 January 
-- recorded] 
  [Text] [Reporter] Can you say if the document that was 
signed by the three presidents in the Kremlin today will have to 
be ratified by the Ukrainian parliament? Will it help resolve 
the issue of disarmament in general, both in Europe and on CIS 
territory? Is this primarily a new step or not? Third, to what 
extent will it help Ukraine's economy? 
  [Kravchuk] The document is a continuation of the Ukrainian 
Supreme Council resolutions. If you recall, the reservations 
that it put forth were about compensation for tactical and 
strategic nuclear weapons, their technical maintenance, 
financial and technical aid, and security guarantees. These, 
approximately, were the main reservations of the Supreme 
Council. When you read that document, and it will be published, 
you will find that all of those demands were met. In other 
words, we can positively state that the executive branch has not 
been acting contrary to the Supreme Council resolutions but 
acting toward fulfilling the reservations put forth by the 
Supreme Council. I would like to emphasize this fact so that no 
one thinks, as some try to imply, that the president and the 
parliament were following their own separate courses. We did 
satisfy the reservations. I said in the past -- and I am 
confirming it now -- that we must join the Nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty. This is my deep conviction, because 
everyone has already joined it -- Russia, Belarus, Kazakhstan, 
and 131 countries. This is a normal step for Ukraine. This is 
why I hope that when we inform our parliament about our actions 
since December... [pauses] a very difficult time for Ukraine, 
which had to withstand pressure from all over the world. Not 
everyone understood our steps, not everyone understood our 
actions and there were grounds for this. This, I think, is a 
matter of principle. Now about your question as to who this 
document will serve. Both the talks with the U.S. President in 
Kiev and the trilateral talks have confirmed one irrefutable 
truth -- problems can be resolved only on the path of 
compromises and agreements. No reservations, no guarantees 
expressed in documents or agreements or declarations or anything 
else will be realized if one or another state follows the policy 
of confrontation instead of compromise. If, for instance, 
Ukraine... [pauses] now they say that Ukraine has been brought 
to its knees. This is absurd. First, Ukraine has come out of 
the situation with credit. We will be compensated and given 
assistance; we will be respected politically and in other ways. 
If we had opposed the adopted course and stood in the way of 
nuclear disarmament -- and it was anticipated -- if Ukraine had 
failed to fulfill its obligations, it would have blocked the 
further development of nuclear disarmament. It would have 
blocked it. START II depends on the resolution of the START I 
issue. I hope that there will be START III as well, and the 
final goal will be achieved in the total dismantling of nuclear 
weapons on our planet. Thus, Ukraine, having resolved this 
issue, unblocked nuclear disarmament for the whole world, for 
all of humanity. By taking this step Ukraine testified to the 
fact that there are no separate paths for Ukraine -- it follows 
the path of civilization and all human interest. This is the 
main issue for all the European and world community. By taking 
this step we have raised Ukraine's political prestige and image, 
we have confirmed that Ukraine's policies are predictable. 
  Finally, there is one more point. Whatever they might say, 
there is an arrangement of forces in the world, an arrangement 
along political lines. And today, great powers are standing as 
the cornerstones of these forces and lines, including the United 
States of America. Relations among states develop depending on 
the influence made by these great powers. Whether one likes it 
or not, that's the way it is. Ambitions are out of place here. 
This is not a policy but just the basic way of thinking. If we 
-- contrary to the world's civilized development -- failed to 
accept compromises...[pauses] it does not mean that we have been 
humiliated; we have compromised, but the other party has also 
made compromises. Thus, we established normal relations. 
  Let us imagine that Ukraine opposes the good will of other 
states, the good will of the world-wide development of nuclear 
disarmament, and the interests of the world states. However, 
not just their interests, but the common interests of mankind -- 
nuclear disarmament. This is important, because we can take 
into account the interests of the state. However, it will not 
coincide with the interests of mankind. 
  What will be the international opinion of Ukraine? We, three 
presidents, of the United States, Ukraine, and Russia -- have 
reached an agreement and solved the issue in a civilized manner, 
in line with the reservations and the interests of the people of 
Ukraine. There are also economic perspectives opening for us; 
this was mentioned by President Clinton in Kiev. In other 
words, Ukraine is seen as a state that took those brakes off, 
enabling cooperation with the United States, with international 
financial organizations, and with Russia. Our acting prime 
minister, Yukhym Leonidovych Zvyahilskyy, and Defense Minister 
Radetskyy met today with their Russian counterparts and resolved 
a wide range of specific issues. Because, this [as heard] is the 
main barrier. Why is it the main barrier? Take for example, 
the military and technical side of the whole matter. We have 
nuclear weapons that we inherited, but we do not produce. 
Everyone, who understands at least something about this is 
aware that we are not capable of servicing them, providing 
maintenance. We just cannot keep them as a heavy burden on our 
shoulders. We cannot maintain them with due responsibility for 
our future and the future of our neighbors and all mankind. 
This has been proven by specialists and by everyone. Those who 
do not understand this are the ones who do not want to. 
  Who is servicing nuclear weapons today? Russia. Well, when 
the president of Russia says: If you want to have nuclear 
weapons, why should we service them? He is right, is he not? 
This is a military and technical aspect. Further, look at the 
aspect of the use of nuclear weapons. Everybody knows it, and 
our minister said this, that some time in 1999 the service life 
of the nuclear weapons would expire. Excuse me, I am telling 
the entire nation that no reservations, no resolutions or edicts 
will prevent [as heard] the president, the defense minister, or 
the government when the service life of these horrible weapons 
expires. We are obliged to remove them because they are more 
dreadful than all the Chernobyl-type accidents taken together. 
And those people who accuse the executive authority today -- 
they either do not understand this or take advantage so as to 
confirm their particular policy, their particular course. 
  There is yet another aspect. Take, for example, most 
superficial things. They say that recoding is possible, that 
something can be done to retain the nuclear arsenal as a 
deterrent. First, when it comes to the issue of recoding, it 
cannot be an abstract code. A question arises: Who is to be 
given the new code? Well, you ask those extreme forces -- they 
will tell you who -- I do not want to repeat the words. But the 
one who is to be given the new code -- will he wait until we 
finish recoding? What if someone would like it to be done, 
suddenly? 
  Second, nuclear weapons require a nuclear industry. Without 
it these are not nuclear weapons. If all this is summed 
up...[pauses] and also it is necessary to have testing grounds 
to carry out tests. We do not have these. There is a whole 
complex of problems facing Ukraine. 
  The situation can be assessed as follows: We have nuclear 
weapons. You do not touch us because if you come and do 
something suddenly, they can explode spontaneously, therefore 
you risk dying, together with us. In other words, this is an 
inhuman act. We have a dangerous thing in our hands which may 
explode. If it explodes and an opponent dies, it is his 
business, he himself makes his way to such an end. But he wants 
millions of people to die, our neighbors included. Who can put 
up with this? Who can regard this as normal? I cannot stop 
wondering if this is a political game, if this is an election 
game -- one can understand this somehow. But it is necessary to 
sit down at a table, place facts here and facts there. If these 
are facts they are facts. But if these are mere words and 
appeals, and deception of the people who experienced the 
Chernobyl catastrophe -- who knows what it is -- if these are 
attempts to put our people in jeopardy, presenting the people of 
the young state -- which is just in the making -- as a monster 
to the whole world, so that they would not recognize it in 
Europe and the world. This is not serious. This is why I think 
that this is our political, economic, humanistic victory. 
  This is our victory. Not mine, not Ukraine's but our common 
victory. The victory of Ukraine, Russia, the United States of 
America, the victory of the entire world. If we all maintain 
friendship and normal relations with Russia and the United 
States and others, we will have our guarantees. But to oppose 
this, and exhibiting our high ambitions and proceeding from 
postulates having nothing to do with the understanding of the 
situation may be dangerous. 
  I am happy with one matter: Those particularly vocal about 
this are a minority and they demonstrate their total ignorance, 
and second, presenting themselves as patriots they, as a matter 
of fact, do not help Ukraine with their actions, to put it 
mildly. 
  [Reporter, HOLOS UKRAYINY newspaper] Leonid Makarovych, I 
have a question. The answer to it concerns many people: Will 
our state's national security be consolidated after today's 
signing [of the trilateral agreement]? If so, what changes for 
the better can be expected? 
  [Kravchuk] It will be consolidated in the following aspect: 
We have already experienced a completely different attitude 
toward Ukraine--from Russia, for example. You have seen a 
different attitude toward us by the United States during the 
U.S. President's visit. I also have reports that NATO countries 
have come to understand Ukraine after receiving the bit of 
information which we still have to think over today. This way, 
the international environment and our neighbors have accepted 
Ukraine as a state that does not want evil but wants to live in 
friendship, partnership, and cooperation with other countries. 
This is the first point. Second, you understand that it is an 
illusion to say that the weapons we have owned were a deterrent. 
I have already told you about this deterrence; this is just a 
danger of deterrence rather than the deterrent. Because we are 
unable to produce, operate, restore, or service them--because we 
have nothing: neither industry nor testing grounds--what kind of 
deterrence can we talk about? This is an illusion of 
deterrence, but it was hammered into people's heads. The 
weapons have not been a guarantee of security, but a source of 
threat--and not only to Ukraine. This way, having won support 
from certain people and states, including powerful states, we 
have obtained security. Security does not mean signed 
documents. You know how many pacts have already been signed in 
history, how many other documents have been signed. However, 
they have been insufficient because a state policy has been 
against what has been signed. We want our policy to be 
implemented in real terms, in line with our civilized and 
anticipated concept, which has been approved. I am convinced 
that we have obtained security and opened the path to economic 
cooperation. We have also achieved a state's image. We have 
acted in line with our Supreme Council, and I am convinced that 
the majority of the people of Ukraine want this. 
  [Reporter] At the recent news conference with Moldovan 
President Snegur you said something like this: The danger 
coming from the revanchist forces in Russia has increased. If 
such factors in the policy of our neighbor dominate, how do you 
think the signed agreement can be fulfilled and what mechanism 
of ensuring our national security do you see as the head of 
state? 
  [Kravchuk] Well, first, I said this a little differently. I 
said I felt anxiety. [passage indistinct] However, the words 
danger and anxiety have subtle differences in connotation. 
Danger means that this is somewhere here... [pauses] As far as 
anxiety is concerned, it is known to me, and every person must 
feel it when complicated processes are under way. However, I 
will repeat that this is not a state policy but a political 
trend. Political trends have occurred in history, you know 
about that. Let us take the last 300 years, and we will find 
different trends in all spheres of social life: spiritual and 
political spheres, and this is a normal democratic phenomenon. 
However, such a tendency must not become a state policy. To 
prevent this, we must cooperate first of all with Russia. There 
are 205 million of us in Russia and Ukraine. Difficult processes 
are under way in our country too. One should not attribute them 
only to Russia. They are everywhere. Revanchists, nationalists, 
national patriots reveal themselves everywhere; they are coming 
out, because such is the time now. Let us prevent them from 
standing in the way of progressive development. This is a 
democratic way. However, to prevent this from becoming a state 
policy is our responsibility and our common concern. When we 
say that we have signed an agreement by three presidents today, 
this speaks volumes. Normal cooperation begins from this point: 
politically, economically, and spiritually. Those forces that 
today are in opposition will remain there. Opposition must 
exist, and there is nothing scary about this. However, one must 
not allow aggressiveness, and antipeople, antihumanitarian 
moods, hidden under patriotism, to dominate in society. We must 
not allow this. That is to say, I feel anxiety but I also have 
hope, because 14 January is a new page of understanding our 
problems, and a page comprised of new steps. I believe that 
these steps are aimed against what makes all of us apprehensive. 
  [Reporter] At a brief news conference today the President 
of the United States of America noted that by signing the 
documents Ukraine has acquired...[pauses] has become more 
influential, has acquired more significance among countries of 
the world, and that many states will now cooperate with Ukraine. 
Moreover, Kostikov, press secretary of Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin, informed journalists that Great Britain is supposedly 
giving us security guarantees already. Is this true? 
  [Kravchuk] Great Britain has given us security guarantees 
previously, but they were not formalized [ne oformleni]. You 
remember when I visited Great Britain: In the treaty I signed 
with the prime minister of Great Britain, it was noted that 
Great Britain--I do not remember the exact formula [word 
indistinct] -- grants Ukraine guarantees from the point of view 
of national security. However, this was an abstract formula. 
Now, the interpretation in the documents we signed is that both 
Great Britain and France I hope, and others will join in with 
this. But I want to repeat: Life is life. There are our 
hopes, opinions, our philosophical understanding of life in this 
world and society, but there are also practical actions. If we 
act practically and in an understandable way, we will in the end 
understand ourselves. I see that we take many steps that are 
difficult to explain. I will frankly say that December was 
possibly the most difficult time in our life for Ukraine, 
because the issue was real, not ephemeral or illusionary. The 
issue was the real international isolation of Ukraine, and this 
meant... I do not even want to use these words. But, for 
example, under a slogan of ultrapatriotism, all this is 
forgotten and people are deceived that Ukraine can survive in 
isolation or confrontation, or by conducting a policy aimed 
against states [word indistinct] and the interests of mankind. 
This is the truth, and everyone knows it. Excuse me, not 
everyone. Those who want to know -- know this. Those who do 
not want to know, or those who know but think differently, will 
never understand anyone. Due to that, this is what I believe. 
  [Reporter] Mr. President, you used the words abstract 
formula 
to describe the agreement (?and so on). However, the statement 
saying that we have gained friends such as the United States and 
Russia also sounds abstract. Will you specify how those 
agreements you signed in Moscow guarantee Ukraine's security. 
  [Kravchuk] First, let us put it this way. It is precisely 
noted that Russia and Ukraine [as heard] respect territorial 
integrity, the inviolability of borders, sovereignty, and 
independence of Ukraine. They respect and support Ukraine's 
independence, and this was stated by President Clinton. He 
always begins his speeches with the statement that Ukraine's 
independence is an important element of U.S. foreign policy. 
This is the first point. The second one is: If we join the 
Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty, those guarantees will acquire a 
more specific, I would say precise, nature, since today we are 
an undefined state. We have inherited nuclear weapons. We can 
neither use nor handle them, and I have talked about this, but 
we have not joined the treaty. What do we really want? Do we 
want to proliferate them or sell them? What do we want? The 
treaty has been joined by 131 countries. We must join the 
treaty. Then, the guarantees will acquire real meaning. 
Because they might ask us: Why do you want guarantees if you 
are a nuclear state? You can attack someone, not be attacked. 
This is an illusion, a nonsense that has developed in 
political... [pauses] I would say that this is political 
dualism, of which everyone is sick and tired. Only one who 
never wants to see anything does not see this. This is the 
point. Therefore, it is noted there. Additionally, an entire 
chapter was devoted to the economic situation, which gives 
Ukraine a real opportunity to join Europe's economic structure, 
including with Russia--(?no, not including)--but in the east 
with Russia, and with other states. An economic space is 
opening up, an international financial space. We are received 
as a state that fulfills its obligations, which were announced, 
by the way, during its independence. I would say that it is not 
prestigious for a state to jump from one point to another, even 
more so, in such a delicate and global sphere as nuclear 
(?weapons). 
  [UNIAN correspondent] Do you think Ukraine, the United 
States, and Russia put a different value, I mean material value, 
on the nuclear weapons, which again will bring up the issue of 
disarmament? 
  [Kravchuk] I do not think so. The United States, Ukraine, 
and Russia will conduct a joint examination. In addition, we 
already have international estimates on this. This is in no way 
a new thing. Let us say, each kilogram of uranium, its quality, 
there are evaluations, then, subtract the cost for enrichment of 
uranium, and it will be all taken into account. Given the 
mutual desire, I see no problems here. We said the following: We 
fulfill our obligations and you fulfill your obligations. If 
one party stops fulfilling its obligations, then the other party 
automatically stops fulfilling its part. I said this plainly. 
According to the agreement, we, for example, withdraw strategic 
nuclear weapons, 200 warheads, then we automatically receive 
compensation and the compensation for the tactical nuclear 
weapons. If someone somewhere begins to manipulate, we will 
publish a relevant statement that we are being deceived, let us 
speak plainly. However, I hope that under the current consensus 
of three presidents -- and what we achieved -- three presidents 
have signed this agreement -- when I spoke with the U.S. 
leadership they said: Mr. President, we put our honor at 
stake; we put the authority of a great world power at stake. 
For us, it was the most important thing -- exactly what we were 
pressing for. Not because we do not trust Russia. Complex 
processes are going on in Russia, both political and economic 
ones, just like here. So we should reckon with the 
possibilities of collisions and problems. But this is the state 
today that can be a guarantor, both for us and Russia. We have 
entered this system of thinking, this system of creating, this 
system of understanding, which [word indistinct] for the benefit 
of Ukraine. 
  [Correspondent] What is the term for the withdrawal of 
nuclear weapons and what is the compensation for the strategic 
and tactical nuclear weapons? In addition, are our debts for 
oil and gas to be canceled? 
  [Kravchuk] There are two constituents of this issue. The 
question of tactical nuclear weapons will soon be examined by 
experts from the United States, Russia, and Ukraine; they will 
evaluate the price, taking into account the (?weight) of what 
was transferred by us in 1991-92, and afterward we will 
determine the forms of compensation. Our debts will be taken 
into account, too. Compensation for strategic nuclear weapons 
has been determined long ago. The nuclear weapons will be 
withdrawn, say, these 200 warheads, their weight taken into 
account, and Ukraine will receive heat-generating elements for 
nuclear power plants. That is, we agreed as follows: We 
estimate that we will be secured... [pauses] for four or five 
years, will we not? [Kravchuk asks some of his aides] Thus, we 
will have free uranium for our power plants over a period of 
seven years. You should understand how important our power 
engineering is for us... [pauses] All this will be determined on 
the basis of the strict evaluations which will take into account 
our experience, as well as world experience. The term of the 
withdrawal will be adjusted depending on our capabilities. I 
have informed you that in 1999 the service life of all our 
warheads will come to an end. Is that so? [one of Kravchuk's 
aides replies "Yes"] [18 second passage indistinct] (?I would 
not have signed it) if the Supreme Council, say, (?does not now) 
ratify it [words indistinct]. I do not know. The service life 
of warheads [words indistinct] is coming up in March. And I 
know that the unforeseen could occur (?here) -- for Ukraine and 
for the world. (?So am I) going to look at this document? If I 
do not [word indistinct] it today, then I will be told tomorrow 
-- you work it out yourself. What sort of a state will we be in 
then? And who will understand us? What sort of civilized state 
and country, which (?like a savage) [words indistinct]. It is a 
terrible thing that our country brandishes its weapons and has 
no idea what to do with them. I am terrified to listen to some 
of our politicians who know nothing about politics, who do not 
want to know anything and do not want to take heed of anyone, 
and are driven only by their ambitions. Let me now read you a 
verse written by one of the members of the Ukrainian delegation 
wishing our country all the best. I will not name the author 
(?until afterwards). [Words indistinct] has written this verse. 
I want to speak about that [word indistinct], that spiritual, 
about that climate, which existed here when people could see 
that they had done something good for the state, for Ukraine. 
They did not give in, nor (?bend down), nor get down on their 
knees. When all were equal [words indistinct] it is obvious 
when someone is telling the truth and when [words indistinct] 
[Kravchuk reads the verse] 
  It is good. [words indistinct]. Normal people understand 
what has happened now. A page has been turned. A page of new 
thinking has been turned, a new attitude toward Ukraine. And if 
we act consistently, this page will be filled with [word 
indistinct] words. The main thing is that Ukraine has not [as 
heard] started on the road of the great desire of mankind -- to 
get rid of nuclear weapons. (?It was wanted all the time) that 
it becomes a brake and enters history just in this way. And 
those politicians, who are now shouting something different, let 
them listen to those people. I wish you all the best. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

