<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze on Summit, Geneva Abkhazia Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1601004094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2233 
GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1601004094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By GIA-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi, 16 Jan--Speaking to foreign journalists, 
Georgian head of state Eduard Shevardnadze called the 
Russian-U.S. talks in Moscow a significant stage in relations 
between the East and West in the post-Communist period. In his 
opinion, the visit by the U.S. President is an important event 
both for the United States and Russia, and for Europe and all 
the republics of the former Soviet Union. "I an grateful to 
Boris Yeltsin and Bill Clinton and also to NATO for the 
attention paid to Georgia," he stressed. 
  Touching upon the results of the second round of the Geneva 
talks on settling the conflict in Abkhazia, the head of state 
noted that a feasible minimum was achieved in Geneva. "A great 
deal will depend on the resolution of the UN Security Council 
that, in our opinion, should envisage guarantees for 
implementing the commitments," Shevardnadze said. What is 
meant, in particular, is the participation of the peacekeeping 
forces under the aegis of the United States, of observers, and 
of the UN High Commissioner for Refugees. 
  The Georgian leader thinks that the consistent continuation 
of the UN policy in resolving the conflict will speed up the 
process of establishing peace in Abkhazia, taking into account 
the positive role of Russia and the interests of the United 
States, France, Britain, and other countries. 

</TEXT>

