<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Satisfied With Visit to Turkey </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401190294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1740 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401190294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" No. 9 feature] </F>
  [Text] Turkey will grant Georgia additional credit worth 
$50 Mn. The understanding was reached Thursday during the visit 
to Turkey by Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze, Interfax was 
told by the spokesman for the Georgian leader, Zaza Kandelaki. 
  The visit has shown, he said, that Georgia and Turkey have 
common interests. At the joint news conference in Ankara, 
Shevardnadze, according to the spokesman, said that Turkey is 
taking a real part in stabilizing the Georgian economy. 
  In an interview with reporters at the Tbilisi airport, 
Shevardnadze said that his visit to Turkey following Georgia's 
entry into the Commonwealth of Independent States was very 
important. He emphasized the package of economic problems 
discussed at the talks. The Georgian leader said that there are 
good prospects for the Georgian economy. "If the process of 
stabilization continues in Georgia, we shall receive more 
essential aid from Turkey," he said. 
  The speaker of the parliament of the Ajarian Autonomous 
Republic, Aslan Abashidze, told Interfax that during the visit 
the two sides reached understanding with the Turkish government 
on Turkish energy supplies to Ajaria beginning January 25. Also 
signed were other agreements on cooperation. 

</TEXT>

