<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gamsakhurdia Widow Accuses Ministry of `Misinformation' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401181794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1453 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401181794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Manana Gamsakhurdia, the widow of the former 
Georgian president, told INTERFAX that his family objected not 
only to making the dead body available for a post mortem, but to 
making it available to the Tbilisi regime as well. 
  "The reports of our consent are the Georgian Interior 
Ministry's exercise in misinformation. I have no intention to 
go to Georgia because I have nothing to do with terrorists and 
murderers. I demand that the body be moved to Chechnya for 
burial," Mrs. Gamsakhurdia said. 
  In her words, she was visited by Chechen President Dzhokhar 
Dudayev, who told her that as a mediator he would insist on 
doing as the deceased's family desired. 

</TEXT>

