<H3> <TI>   Laar Says Gaydar Resignation `Turn Backwards' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801205694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1837 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801205694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: No. 11 (501)] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Mart Laar believes that Yegor 
Gaydar's resignation from the Russian government means "a turn 
backwards" in the reform policy pursued by Russia. 
  In his interview with Interfax the premier voiced a 
supposition that certain moods to turn away from shock therapy 
and increase state expenditures for social needs spreading in 
Russia have played a certain role here. 
  "It's a pity that shortage of funds for these purposes could 
result in the refusal of reform policy and very hard 
consequences for all Russia's neighbors, as their successes in 
economic development depend upon their eastern neighbor," 
underlined Laar. 
  "It's strange to hear optimistic statements against such a 
background stating that nothing has changed in Russia and after 
the elections everything is continuing as before," he said. 

</TEXT>

