<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Legislators Pass Health Care Law </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1801183494 Tallinn BNS in English 1630 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1801183494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 18, BNS -- The Estonian parliament 
today adopted the law on the health care system with 45 votes 
for, 11 votes against and six abstentions. The law establishes 
the legal status of the country's medical institutions and the 
basis of financing of the health care system. 
  The law defines medical aid as the activity of doctors with 
a 
higher medical education to protect people's health, prolong 
their lives and improve the quality of life. Medical aid is 
arranged on three levels: general and specialized aid at the 
local government level and specialized medical aid on the 
national level. 
  A national Health Care Council is to be set up under the 
government. General administration and supervision of health 
care will be placed in the hands of the Social Affairs Ministry. 
County medical officers are going to shape the state's health 
care policy on the regional level. They will be appointed for a 
term of five years by county elders, who coordinate the 
nomination with the Social Affairs Ministry. 
  The law on the health care system takes effect on Feb. 15. 
  The legislators amended the law on the relation between the 
local and the state budgets, and continued the second reading of 
the surveillance bill. Also Jaan Luik, a member of the State 
Court, was sworn in. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

