<H3> <TI>   Ulmanis Calls Russian Army Decision `Uncivilized' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801141394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1148 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801141394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis has described as 
uncivilized the decision by the command of Russia's Northwestern 
Army Group to authorize the use of arms for the defense of 
Russian servicemen and army property on Latvian territory. 
  Following the incident with two Russian generals on January 
10, the command of the Northwestern Army Group authorized 
servicemen to shoot to kill to rebuff attempts to seize any army 
facility. 
  Briefing newsmen on January 17, Ulmanis described the 
decision as an uncivilized response to the civilized moves he 
made on January 10. He reminded newsmen that action had been 
taken immediately on his orders for the release of the Russian 
generals, subsequent investigation and punishment of those 
responsible. 
  Ulmanis saw the decision as provocative and a show of force. 
  He hoped it would have no far-reaching repercussions. He 
also saw it as a signal for the Latvian authorities to show more 
caution in what they choose to say or do. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

