<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Council Favors Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701175994 Riga Radio Riga Network in Latvian 1700 GMT 17 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1701175994 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga Radio Riga Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Latvian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis told a news 
conference that at a session today, the Latvian State Security 
Council valued proposals expressed in the framework of the NATO 
program Partnership for Peace. Ulmanis added that an official 
letter to NATO would also be prepared, in which the wish of the 
Latvian side to participate in the program will be expressed. 
The issue of Latvia joining NATO is, however, to be considered 
only in a more distant future. 
  Ulmanis believes initial cooperation with NATO can be in the 
way of training and consultations. The first step toward this 
cooperation from the Latvian side would be working out a unified 
concept for material and technical supplies for the state armed 
structures. 
  The cooperation program also includes the request to be very 
objective and loyal in the issues of human rights, which Latvia 
perceives with great responsibility. Ulmanis added that in the 
framework of the proposed partnership, it would be very 
important to form balanced relations with Russia. 

</TEXT>

