<H3> <TI>   U.S. Official, Ambassador Hold News Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1701140394 Riga Radio Riga Network in Latvian 1300 GMT 17 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1701140394 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga Radio Riga Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Latvian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Name indistinct], a U.S. national security 
representative, and U.S. Ambassador to Latvia Ints Silins held a 
news conference at the U.S. information center today on the 
Partnership for Peace cooperation plan proposed by NATO. It was 
again stressed at the news conference that this NATO program is 
open for all East European states, irrespective of whether they 
have expressed the wish to be involved in NATO. 
  Representatives of the Latvian Government have agreed to 
that 
program. Latvia would also feel more secure if it participates 
in it. 
  Asked why the United States has not reacted to Russia's 
increased military readiness [reference to 10 January 
deportation of two Russian generals], Ambassador Silins noted 
that not all tensions in interstate relations warrant a special 
U.S. statement. 
  At the end, it was once again indicated that the United 
States favors a speedier withdrawal of the Russian Army from 
Latvia. 

</TEXT>

