<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Candidate Holds News Conference </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1901114194 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 0903 GMT 19 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1901114194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Simferopol -- Yuriy Meshkov, leader of the "Russia" 
bloc and candidate for president of the Republic of Crimea, gave 
a news conference yesterday. He received 38.5 percent of the 
vote on 16 January in the first round of elections. Yuriy 
Meshkov told journalists that the persuasive results of the 
voting in Crimea testify to the possibility of improving 
relations between Crimea and Ukraine and put relations with 
Russia on a qualitatively new level. 
  Responding to a question about a possible reaction from 
official Kiev toward new Crimea, Yuriy Meshkov expressed 
confidence in the ability of Leonid Kravchuk, as one of the 
outstanding politicians of the present time, to regulate the 
political situation in Ukraine and beyond. In the words of 
Yuriy Meshkov, the Ukrainian president stated earlier that the 
dislocation of forces in Crimea ruled out a forcible 
intervention from outside, since it would lead to unforeseen 
consequences. "I have no grounds for not trusting Kravchuk," 
Meshkov stressed. 
  In spite of the fact that the central point of Yuriy 
Meshkov's electoral program is the holding of an all-Crimean 
referendum on the status of the peninsula, the presidential 
candidate refrained at the news conference from stating the act 
of will by the Crimeans, but noted that this will, which was 
expressed during the elections on 16 January, should be given 
legal form. [Words indistinct] that the referendum will be held 
on 27 March. 
  Yuriy Meshkov confirmed his position regarding the 
nonacceptance of quotas in the Supreme Council of the Republic 
of Crimea for deported peoples, noting that quotas for Crimean 
Tatars in the future parliament would be a violation of the 
norms of international law. The candidate for president of the 
Crimean Republic described the Assembly of the Crimean Tatars as 
a real civil and political force. He also said that Crimea has 
enough state attributes but not enough state content: "What we 
need are not the outward signs of statehood but the possibility 
of resolving all economic, political, and sociocultural issues 
by taking into maximum account the Crimean Republic's interests." 

</TEXT>

