<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brazauskas: Talks on Kaliningrad Issue To Resume </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801125894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1148 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801125894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lithuanian President Algirdas Brazauskas has 
declared his administration is assigning priority to cooperation 
with other Baltic republics, integration into the political, 
economic and defense structures of Europe, and the promotion of 
neighborly relations, primarily with Russia, Ukraine, and 
Belarus. 
  The President announced this Monday [17 January] to the 
Vilnius-based chiefs of diplomatic missions. 
  He said he was planning to visit Belarus and invite his 
Ukrainian counterpart Leonid Kravchuk to visit Lithuania. 
Treaties on cooperation and neighborly relations were likely to 
be signed as a result of those visits. 
  Algirdas Brazauskas felt relations had improved between his 
republic and Russia. The discussion, he said, would soon resume 
of an agreement on military transits from Russia to the 
Kaliningrad region via Lithuanian territory. 
  The Lithuanian President told diplomats that calls for the 
revision of the Pottsdam conference's decision on the 
Kaliningrad region had nothing to do with his administration's 
official foreign policy line. The calls were coming from 
certain members of the Lithuanian parliament. 

</TEXT>

