<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Polish Ministry Responds on Status of Poles </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1801165294 Tallinn BNS in English 1434 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1801165294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 18, BNS -- The Polish Foreign Ministry 
released a statement in response to a letter signed by 72 Polish 
lawmakers, who expressed concern about the status of Poles in 
Lithuania and the course of talks between the two countries. 
  The letter, addressed to the Polish president, the prime 
minister, the foreign minister and the Polish parliament's 
speaker, appeared in the Lithuanian press last week. The 72 
demand that Poland observe 5 principles when signing an 
agreement on friendship and cooperation with Lithuania. The 
agreement has been under negotiation since last summer. 
  In its statement, the Polish ministry assures lawmakers that 
it is no less concerned about the interests of Poles in 
Lithuania than the Polish parliament. According to the 
statement, the Polish Foreign Ministry holds that Lithuanian 
Poles must be guaranteed equal rights in Lithuania. 
  As previously reported, 72 Polish lawmakers, mainly members 
of the parliamentary majority, demanded to create a cultural 
autonomy of the predominantly Polish-populated Vilnius and 
Salcininkai regions, to return nationalized property to Polish 
social organizations, to exclude history from the main agreement 
with Lithuania, etc. 

</TEXT>

