<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Landsbergis Sees Improvement in Ties With Poland </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1801163394 Tallinn BNS in English 1050 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1801163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 18, BNS -- Possibilities have appeared 
for Lithuania and Poland to reach an agreement, said Vytautas 
Landsbergis, leader of the Lithuanian parliament's rightist 
opposition. 
  At a press conference Monday [17 January], Landsbergis 
commented on a meeting of Polish and Lithuanian politicians, 
scholars and representatives of social organizations, held in 
Warsaw Saturday. The meeting's participants focused on common 
political interests of both countries and also discussed the 
problem of Russian military force in the Kaliningrad region. 
Lithuanian and Polish politicians must seek the region's 
demilitarization, Landsbergis said. In his opinion, the struggle 
against the emerging Russian imperialism could also be a common 
interest, as well as Lithuania's rapproachement with the 
Visegrad Treaty (Poland, Slovakia, Hungary and the Czech 
Republic). 
  The opposition leader specified some reports that Poland 
regrets the absence of an agreement on friendship and 
cooperation with Lithuania. Landsbergis said the Lithuanian side 
emphasizes the need to sign a separate declaration on the 1920 
occupation of the Vilnius region by Poland together with the 
main agreement. 
  Landsbergis said Polish Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak 
expressed hope that the problem will soon be solved. 
  The opposition leader said the Polish side apologized 
several 
times for a letter to President Lech Walesa, signed by 72 
members of the Polish parliamentary majority. As previously 
reported, the letter suggests very categorical terms of signing 
the agreement. Landsbergis said an apology was also made by the 
chairman of the Polish party in power. 
  "Possibilities to agree do exist, but there are opponents 
who 
seek to prevent this." 

</TEXT>

