<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brazauskas Meets With Foreign Diplomats </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1801170494 Tallinn BNS in English 1434 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1801170494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 18, BNS -- Lithuanian President 
Algirdas Brazauskas wished "many good relations" to foreign 
diplomats accredited to Lithuania and thanked Western countries 
for their support in the process of the Russian troop withdrawal 
from Lithuania. 
  The president's annual meeting with foreign diplomats in 
Vilnius Monday [17 January] was attended by 29 ambassadors and 
charges d'affaires residing both in Lithuania and other 
countries. 
  Commenting on Lithuania's steps toward European political, 
economic and cultural systems, Brazauskas said his country does 
not want a borderline to be drawn between blocs either "to the 
east or to the west of Lithuania." He said Lithuania's official 
request to be admitted to NATO does not mean that the present 
state of relations with Russia and other Eastern countries would 
be altered. 
  The president said "some things were done to improve 
relations with Russia" last year, but a number of problems still 
await solutions. 
  Brazauskas said he categorically opposes suggestions to 
review the decisions made at the Potsdam conference, especially 
those concerning the Kaliningrad region. As regards the region, 
Lithuanian-Russian relations are good, he said, but added that 
Kaliningrad must be demilitarized by "that country" (Russia). 
  Discussing Lithuania's domestic policy, Brazauskas expressed 
hope that a stable government will be preserved because there 
have been no serious arguments for holding early parliamentary 
elections. In his opinion, the country's economy has stabilized 
and some success has been achieved in the struggle against crime. 
  During his discussion with Reinhard Kraus, German ambassador 
to Lithuania, the president mentioned his intention to visit 
Germany this year. 
  Brazauskas also announced his intention to invite the 
Ukrainian president to Lithuania and to visit Minsk himself. 
  A letter from the Italian president was presented to 
Brazauskas by Franco Tempesta, Italian ambassador to Lithuania, 
but the Lithuanian president's press service was unable to say 
anything about its contents. 

</TEXT>

