<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aliyev Blames Former Leaders for Troop Presence </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801203694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1809 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801203694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Azerbaijani President Gaydar Aliyev declared that 
introduction of Soviet forces on January 20, 1990, would have 
been impossible if Baku's former leadership had not permitted 
forces to be introduced. 
  As many as 132 people were killed during those January days 
and more than 700 were wounded. 
  The president voiced his remark during the report of 
Azerbaijan's attorney general Ali Omarov. Omarov, in 
particular, pointed out that the purpose for forces being 
introduced into Baku at that time was primarily to rescue the 
leadership of Azerbaijan's communist party. 
  As the attorney general believes, Azerbaijan's former 
leaders 
Abdurakhman Vezirov, Ayaz Mutalibov, Viktor Polyanichko, Elmira 
Gafarova, and former leader of the republic's KGB Vagif Gusaynov 
should be made answerable for the January 1990 events along with 
the former Soviet leadership at that time and its power 
ministers (Gorbachev, Yazov, Kryuchkov, Bakatin, Primakov). 
  Omarov reported that he had ordered the National Security 
Ministry to institute proceedings against Vagif Gusaynov due to 
the January 20, 1990, events in Baku. 
  Observers do not rule out that criminal charges against 
Vezirov and Mutalibov can be brought as well. 
  The discussion is being continued. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

