<H3> <TI>   To Meet in Moscow 25 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1801223794 Baku TURAN in English 0820 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC1801223794 </F>
<F P=104>  Baku TURAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, January 17 [date as received] (TURAN)--The 
meeting between Azerbaijani and Armenian presidents has been 
planned for January 25 in Moscow with the Russian side serving 
as mediator, a reliable source at the Russian Foreign Ministry 
told TURAN's reporter. 
  According to information available, Moscow has organized the 
talks at the request of the Armenian side. Another attempt to 
bring about a change in the political regulation of the 
Armenian-Azeri conflict will be made at the meeting with the 
participation of Russian President Boris Yeltsin. 
  A pre-meeting dialogue by the heads of foreign offices of 
Azerbaijan and Armenia will take place in Moscow as well. 
  The questions discussed by the foreign ministers will be the 
same for the presidents. 
  Diplomatic experts believe that Moscow and Yerevan will try 
to force Baku to agree to a plan that has been worked out by the 
adviser of the Russian president, Andranik Migranian [name as 
received]. According to this plan, Azerbaijan will have to 
guarantee the granting of status of broad self-government and 
the according political status to Nagorno-Karabakh. The plan's 
terms also include the creation of the so-called "humanitarian 
corridors" from Armenia to Nagorno-Karabakh through Lachin and 
Kelbadzhar in exchange for peace. 
  Moreover, this plan envisions the creation of a 
"demilitarized zone" along all the perimeter of 
Nagorno-Karabakh." 
  The proposal also envisages measures providing regular 
transport of energy and free flow of communications in the 
Transcaucasian region. In particular, the plan also sees the 
creation of a railroad command post that would provide strict 
management of the railways. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

