<F P=102>  LD1801205594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1723 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801205594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze on Tuesday [18 
January] ordered the republic's Military Prosecutor's Office to 
take measures to return to Russian Armed Forces officers in 
Tbilisi and other cities apartments from which they have been 
forcibly evicted. 
  According to Shevardnadze's press service, there are 104 
such 
apartments, most of which have been seized by Georgian military 
officers, who threaten to use arms if any attempt is made to 
evict them. 
  A source in the press center of Russia's Armed Forces Group 
in the Transcaucasus told Interfax this was the first time the 
Georgian authorities had taken up the matter. If Shevardnadze's 
orders to give back the apartments were ignored, relations 
between Russian and Georgian troops could deteriorate, the 
source said. 

</TEXT>

