<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Briefs Press </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1701132994 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 15 Jan 94 
First Edition p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM1701132994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS report: "Vladimir Shumeyko: Intrigues Will Be </F>
Excluded"] 
  [Text] Vladimir Shumeyko has given his first press 
conference as chairman of the Russian Federation Federal 
Assembly Federation Council. 
  Replying to journalists' questions, the speaker of the upper 
house called the situation which had arisen during the ballot 
"routine teething troubles." In his opinion, they were due to 
the fact that, on the one hand, members of the Federation 
Council did not want to bring matters to the point of 
confrontation, but, on the other hand, there are people among 
them with different, at times diametrically opposed, political 
views. The speaker stated that he would seek to exclude various 
lobby intrigues from the Federation Council. 
  Vladimir Shumeyko also dwelt on the question of relations 
between the upper house and the State Duma, in particular, in 
the event that the lower house adopts, for whatever reasons, an 
unconstructive stance. He recalled that, under the 
Constitution, in addition to the president, the government, and 
State Duma deputies, the Federation Council as a whole and 
individual members of the Federation Council also possess 
legislative initiative. In that case, he stressed, it is 
possible, in cooperation with Duma deputies who really desire to 
do something, to elaborate legislative acts in joint committees 
and commissions and adopt them straightaway right here. 
Vladimir Shumeyko clarified that he was talking of "an extreme 
case" and "bitter necessity." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

