<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rybkin Comments on Role as Chairman of Duma </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401174994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1645 
GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1401174994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 14 Jan -- "The chairman of the State Duma 
absorbs the opinions of all the deputies and no proposal made by 
a deputy should be left unnoticed," Ivan Rybkin, the chairman of 
the lower chamber of the Federal Assembly, stated today at a 
news conference. "The speaker should rise above his party 
allegiance, otherwise he is simply not ready to occupy this 
post," he added. 
  In Rybkin's opinion, the chairman of the Duma should 
organize 
the work of the lower chamber in such a way as ensure that the 
most topical problems receive sufficient legislative support. 
He believes that our legislation does not keep pace with life. 
  The speaker of the Duma said that putting our economic 
legislation in line with realities of life should become its 
priority task. He also stressed that it is necessary to study 
proposals prepared by the Commission for Legislative Proposals 
attached to the Russian President. "It made many valuable 
proposals," believes Ivan Rybkin. Apart from that, the chairman 
of the Duma sees its task in solving the question of the state 
financing of the parties via their factions in the lower chamber 
of the Federal Assembly, as well as maintaining interaction with 
those parties whose representatives were not elected to the 
parliament. 
  "The main committees of the Duma should be formed in 
proportion to factions' numbers," believes Rybkin. At the same 
time, he noted that "leaders of the deputies' associations today 
are unlikely to agree to act as heads of the committees because 
they already have enough organizational work to do in the 
factions and deputies' associations." 
  Speaking about the economic reform in the country, Ivan 
Rybkin stressed that they need some corrections. "We should be 
searching for more intelligent solutions that suit the Russian 
realities," he believes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-56655 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov012_c_94012" </HT>


