<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shokhin Warns Opponents May Make State Duma Useless </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1401215294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1705 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1401215294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Velichko] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 14 TASS -- "The major threat to the 
State Duma is the State Duma itself," Vice-Premier Aleksandr 
Shokhin told correspondents here today. 
  He said the Russian Constitution requires two thirds of 
votes 
to adopt a law. According to the Fundamental Law, regular laws 
should be adopted by the majority of State Duma deputies, which 
is 223 Duma members in its current composition. 
  A law can be returned for improvement if the upper 
parliament 
chamber does not approve it or the law is vetoed by the 
president. The veto can be annulled by only two thirds of votes. 
Thus, the deputies should learn to overcome faction differences. 
  "The State Duma may be turned by the opponents into a 
useless 
body, and the constitution carries a mechanism of its 
dissolution," said the vice-premier. 
  He is sure the lower parliament chamber should turn into a 
"normal efficient body and abandon extremism". Cold War 
elements evident in the very second day of Duma functioning 
should be stopped. "If the Duma manages to overcome faction 
ambitions and learns to predict behavior of the upper chamber, 
it will be able to influence the legislative power," he stressed. 
  Shokhin stated with regret some factions did not manage to 
protect interests of the Duma minority. A proposal to organize 
20- deputy factions was voted down. The vice-premier expressed 
the assurance the more independent territorial deputy groups are 
formed they would be considered potentially conciliatory 
mechanisms. 
  In the opinion of the vice-premier, some small factions have 
agreed with large ones on certain distribution of posts in the 
lower chamber. "This cannot be viewed as a mere expression of 
will, it is rather a normal parliamentary agreement between 
factions. It is a good lesson to other parties in the ability 
to reach an agreement," said Shokhin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-56657 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov012_c_94014" </HT>


