<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia, U.S. To Fulfill Uranium Contract </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801125194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1148 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801125194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia and the U.S., which signed a contract for 
deconcentrating highly enriched uranium last week, will fulfill 
it without Ukraine's participation, a senior official from 
Russia's Nuclear Energy Ministry told INTERFAX. 
  The contract for deconcentrating 500 tons of highly enriched 
uranium was concluded to develop the agreement signed by the two 
sides last February, the source said. Its implementation will 
take 20 years. 
  The contract provides for deconcentrating annually at least 
10 tons of Russian uranium, which will subsequently be sold on 
the American market. Its cost will be 12 Bn dollars. 
  According to the official, the delay in signing the document 
was connected with Washington's condition that Ukraine, Belarus 
and Kazakhstan should be involved in implementing the agreement. 
  However, later it was agreed that the uranium from Ukrainian 
nuclear warheads will be returned to Ukraine as fuel for nuclear 
power plants, and will not be despatched to the American market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

