<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Supports Achievement of Karabakh Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801191094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1552 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801191094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature] </F>
  [Text] Russia stands for achieving "a cease-fire in the 
area of the Armenian-Azeri conflict at any price," the political 
adviser to the head of Russian diplomacy, Galina Sidorova, told 
Interfax on Tuesday after a meeting between Andrey Kozyrev and 
his Azeri counterpart, Gasan Gasanov, in Moscow. 
  Kozyrev and Gasanov, she said, discussed the possibility of 
a 
cease-fire and signing an agreement between Armenia and 
Azerbaijan as soon as possible. 
  As Sidorova said, negotiations between the two sides are 
progressing with difficulty, since many grievances and 
suspicions have built up between them during the conflict. 
  According to Sidorova, "a further escalation of hostilities 
is dangerous not only for the two nations which are actually 
engaged in annihilating each other: It poses a threat to 
stability in the region as a whole. That is why foremost 
importance is attached to the need to stop military actions," 
she said. 
  The head of Russian diplomacy may also confer with Armenia's 
Foreign Minister, Vagan Papazian, in Moscow in the near future, 
Sidorova said. 
  It is possible that the Presidents of Russia, Armenia and 
Azerbaijan - Boris Yeltsin, Levon Ter-Petrosyan and Geydar 
Aliyev, will meet in Moscow before the end of this month. 

</TEXT>

