<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Meets Milosevic, Tudjman in Geneva </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801224294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2115 
GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1801224294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Konstantin Pribytkov] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, 18 Jan -- Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy 
Churkin, the Russian president's special representative, met in 
Geneva today with Serb President Slobodan Milosevic and Croatian 
President Franjo Tudjman; Thorvald Stoltenberg and David Owen, 
co-chairmen of the coordinating committee of the conference on 
the former Yugoslavia; and Charles Redman, representing the U.S. 
Administration. The consultations enabled a wide range of 
problems relating to the conflict in Bosnia and Herzegovina to 
be discussed. 
  Vitaliy Churkin told the ITAR-TASS correspondent that the 
current round of talks on the Bosnian settlement, which started 
in Geneva on Tuesday [18 January], "is progressing with 
difficulty." "The aggravation of the situation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina provides unfavorable conditions for the 
negotiating process," said the Russian representative. 
"Nevertheless, there are some bright spots. It seems that we 
have managed to resolve the problem of replacing Canadian blue 
helmets with the Dutch in Srebrenica, the UN security zone. We 
are satisfied with this development and expect no further 
problems." 

</TEXT>

