<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia To Supply India With Cryogen Boosters </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801190294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1632 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801190294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by diplomatic correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboinikov, </F>
Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy Trubetskoy, and others; from the 
"Diplomatic Panorama" feature] 
  [Text] Russia continues to actively cooperate with India's 
National Space Agency and is prepared to supply it with seven 
contracts, the Director General of Russia's Space Agency, Yuri 
Koptev, told Interfax. 
  According to him, the $220 Mn contract signed with the 
former 
USSR remains virtually the same amount, even though Moscow had 
to give up the supplies of booster technologies stipulated in 
the contract. 
  According to Koptev, Russia agreed to shoulder some of the 
commitments connected with India's space program. For instance, 
it is prepared to supply cryogen boosters (i.e. the last stage 
of the booster rocket) for India's Geostationary Satellite 
Launch Vehicles. 
  In addition, Russia has signed a contract worth $28 Mn for 
the production and supply of equipment to service cryogen 
booster systems. 

</TEXT>

