<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Elections Begin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1601095594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0926 GMT 16 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1601095594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Shanayev] </F>
  [Text] Vladikavkaz January 16 TASS -- North Ossetia is 
holding its first ever presidential elections on Sunday. At 
7:00 A.M., 300 polling stations located in cities, regional 
centres and remote mountainous villages opened to receive first 
electors. The voting will continue until 20:00 P.M. 
  Two candidates have been put on ballot papers, including 
chairman of the North Ossetian parliament Akhsarbek Galazov and 
head of the North Ossetian government, Sergey Khetagurov. 
  For the time being, Galazov has the highest rating, 
according 
to the results of a sociological poll, ITAR-TASS learned from 
the Central Electoral Commission. The turn-out as reported by 
10:00 A.M. was average. The people are casting their ballots in 
a calm atmosphere and no violations of the franchise have been 
reported. 
  Galazov has already voted at polling station No. 189 in 
Vladikavkaz. Asked by a journalist which candidate he had 
crossed out from his ballot paper, Galazov said "one of the two". 
  Talking to representatives of the mass media, Galazov said 
that "the elections of the first North Ossetian president should 
consolidate the multinational population of the republic and 
give a positive impetus to reforms in economy and a political 
life." 
  It was earlier reported that in connection with the 
elections 
of the North Ossetian president a state of emergency in North 
Ossetia and Ingushetia had been suspended for twenty four hours 
in accordance with the Russian president's decree. Russian 
peace- keeping forces have been instructed to maintain law and 
order in public places during this period of time and take 
measures to ensure citizens' safety. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

