<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Resignation Denied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801184194 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1700 GMT 
18 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1801184194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] INTERFAX has reported the end of the meeting between 
the Russian president and the head of the government, at which 
the question of the make-up of the new cabinet of ministers was 
discussed in particular. The meeting lasted six and a half 
hours, but no decision on the personnel composition of the 
government was taken. 
  From the Kremlin, Boris Yeltsin and Viktor Chernomyrdin went 
off to their dachas. 
  Deputy Prime Minister Aleksandr Shokhin, INTERFAX reports, 
told journalists today that Viktor Chernomyrdin had offered him 
a choice of two posts in the new government -- minister for CIS 
affairs or economics minister. Shokhin is going to announce his 
decision tomorrow. 
  Today too, Sergey Shakhray, another deputy prime minister, 
stated, according to the POSTFAKTUM agency, that he had been 
offered the post of minister of nationality affairs and regional 
policy. It is not yet known whether he has accepted the offer. 
  Meanwhile Boris Fedorov's press secretary denied a report 
that he has resigned. In a RIA interview, the press secretary 
said, literally, the following: Boris Grigoryevich has not 
accepted the prime minister's proposal that he should retain 
just the post of finance minister, but neither has he resigned. 

</TEXT>

