<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Likely To Be Formed Without Fedorov </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1801210694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1805 GMT 18 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1801210694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" No. 11 feature] </F>
  [Text] According to Interfax's sources, President Boris 
Yeltsin and Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin are now 
discussing the set up of a new Russian government. 
  The president had accepted the resignation of Yegor Gaydar 
who told Interfax that he more or less knew who would be serve 
in the government. In his view, Vice Premier Anatoliy Chubays, 
a member of Russia's Choice, should not resign while Vice 
Premier and Finance Minister Boris Fedorov should. 
  Officials in Fedorov's secretariat told Interfax Tuesday 
that 
he had rejected the prime minister's offer to stay as finance 
minister in the reorganized government but had not resigned 
either of his positions. 
  When he met Chernomyrdin Monday, Fedorov demanded special 
powers in pursuing his financial and economic policy "in line 
with what he was promised when he was appointed vice premier in 
1992." 
  Fedorov told Interfax that he could stay "as just the 
finance 
minister" if there was just one first premier, Oleg Soskovets, 
but not if there are four or five vice premiers. 
  He confirmed that he had also demanded that Aleksandr 
Zaveryukha should not be a vice premier and Viktor Gerashchenko, 
governor of the Central Bank of Russia. 
  Fedorov's aides told Interfax that he sent a letter to 
Yeltsin Tuesday morning outlining his view of the situation and 
conditions on which he would agree to stay in the government. 
  Meanwhile, an informed source in the government told 
Interfax 
that Chernomyrdin had decided not to have Fedorov in the 
government "on his conditions." 
  The same source says that this opinion is shared by the 
president. 

</TEXT>

